<HEAD>Police Use Water Cannon, Tear Gas as General Strike Hits Ecuador</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with reports of
violence, other. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS CISTERNAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police firing water cannons and tear gas broke up street protests in this capital city on Wednesday during a Communist-led general strike that paralyzed transportation. Small pockets of strikers blocked streets with flaming tires and rubble before being driven off. The government said 13 protesters were arrested in <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION>. News reports said six people were detained in <LOCATION> Guayquil </LOCATION>, the nation's financial center and largest city with 2 million people, 180 miles southwest of the capital Interior Minister <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> called the strike a failure. He said nearly all of the nation's labor force of 3 million workers ignored the strike call. <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> told a news conference a capital policeman was injured by a firebomb tossed by a protester. There were no other reports of injury. Strike leader <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> <PERSON> Dutan </PERSON> said 80 percent of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s business activity was halted by the strike, called to back demands for higher pay. Radio reports said the strike had little impact in provincial cities across this Andean nation, which is the size of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and has 10 million people. Strike protests waned as night fell. The downtown of this highland capital of 1.4 million residents was filled with tear gas, making breathing difficult for the few pedestrians left on the streets. President <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> said the strike, the seventh during his tenure, was illegal and declared a nationwide state of emergency. Combat troops were sent to guard electric generating plants, gasoline stations and other installations. Riot police patrolled streets and industrial sectors of <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s major cities. The nationwide strike was organized by the Communist-led <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laborers </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's most powerful labor federation, to seek wage increases. <PERSON> Dutan </PERSON> said the 200,000-member confederation wants the minimum monthly wage raised from $ 31 to $ 76. <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> admitted that bus and taxi service in <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guayaquil </LOCATION> was nearly halted as drivers stayed off the job either in strike sympathy or in fear of violence. Many of <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION>'s factories did not open because workers could not reach their jobs, news reports said. Banks, stores and shops in downtown <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION> opened normally or slightly late but closed in early afternoon to avoid trouble. The government suspended school classes nationwide. <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>, a conservative whose four-year term ends Aug. 10, has faced increasing labor unrest over the past two years amid mounting economic woes, caused mainly by depressed world prices for oil, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s main export. <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Borja </PERSON>, a lawyer who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, won a presidential runoff election in May to replace <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> said the state of emergency, which permits the government to deploy the military, ban public meetings and censor the media, would stay in force only until the strike officially ended at midnight Wednesday.
</TEXT>
