<HEAD>Four Republicans Seek GOP Nomination For U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL FEATHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some Republicans refer to first-term Sen. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> as the `` invisible senator,'' and their conviction that he can be beaten has lured four candidates to seek the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination in the June 7 primary. <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> is vulnerable because of his liberal voting record and his position on national defense issues, said state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lattauzio </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s congressmen philosophically have always supported defense spending until <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> came along,'' he said. `` And economically defense spending is very important to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` If we can articulate these issues effectively, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate will do very well,'' Lattauzio said. `` Another thing we will be able to talk about a lot is that <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> is the ` invisible senator.' New Mexicans are accustomed to their congressmen staying in touch with them,'' Lattauzio said. `` <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> just has n't been around up until recently.'' <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> said in January when he announced for re-election that as one of only two first-term Democrats running this year _ the other is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> _ he expected his race to be targeted by the national <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. But Democrats question whether the Republican field of state Sens. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>, 44, and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Carraro </PERSON>, 43, both of <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, long-time party activist <PERSON> Corky </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, 52, of <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, and former <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruces </LOCATION> can produce a strong challenger to <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON>. Polls showing a high percentage of undecided Republicans, far greater than the percentage favoring any candidate, indicate none of the four has caught fire with the voters. Valentine and <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, however, appear to be the front-runners. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON>, a former state <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairman, said <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> may be vulnerable but not with any of this year's Republican candidates `` Those guys are all wallflowers who follow the old party line,'' <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> said. `` I think had the Republicans had a charismatic candidate running against <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON>, he would have a tough time in the fall.'' <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>, who sold his dentistry practice to campaign fulltime, and <PERSON> Carraro </PERSON>, who owns and operates two pizza restaurants, are giving up their state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats to try for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, who owns trucking and warehousing companies in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, is a former state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> chairman and was <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> chairman of the Reagan-Bush campaign in 1984. <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON> left the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> for terriorities and international affairs to return to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and seek elective office for the first time. <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON>, who is unopposed in the Democratic primary, is a Harvard-educated lawyer who in 1982 defeated first-term Republican Sen. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> `` <PERSON> Jack </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON>, a former astronaut. <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bingaman </PERSON> has recognized his problems and corrected most of them, including that he had not been communicating with his constituency on a regular basis. He also has been spending more time in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in the last year, meeting with residents. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race and presidential voting top <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s primary ballot, but the retirement after 20 years of Republican Rep. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> has thrown open the door in the 1st Congressional District. Three Republicans, including <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>'s younger brother <PERSON> Edward </PERSON>, and nine Democrats aspire to succeed <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, who has called it quits after 20 years in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, 55, is an <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> insurance executive and former state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> chairman. Challenging him are <LOCATION> Bernalillo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiff </PERSON>, 40, of <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> and state Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Budagher </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>. The top Democratic contenders are former state Land Commissioner <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Baca </PERSON>, 42, former state <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Judge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Patricia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, 41, <LOCATION> Bernalillo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissione