<HEAD>Number Of Children In China Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s family planning policy, which calls for no more than one child per couple, has in six years reduced by 30.1 million the number of children under the age of 14, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> said today. The bureau said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> now has 307.15 million children under 14, compared to 337.25 million in 1982. It found the proportion of children in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s total population of 1.07 billion to be 28.68 percent, down from 33.45 percent six years ago, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. The bureau attributed the decline to the family planning policy, which has been largely successful in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s crowded cities but has met resistance in many rural areas, where two or more children is still the norm. The bureau said children account for just 18.36 percent of the population in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest city, while making up 36 percent in the remote western areas of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ningxia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Autonomous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>.
