<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Attorney General <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> B. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> ignored evidence that top <PERSON> E.F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> executives orchestrated a widespread check-kiting scheme when he blamed mid-level managers in a defamatory report, the lawyer for one of those managers says. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a defendant in a defamation suit brought by one of six branch managers he criticized in the 1985 report about the check-kiting scheme, was trying to shift the blame away from top management, the lawyer argued Tuesday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` He cleared the company, he cleared the management and put the blame out on regional managers and branch managers,'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON>, a lawyer for former <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON>, said as the defamation trial got under way. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a private attorney in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, was retained by <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> to conduct the internal investigation after the company pleaded guilty May 2, 1985, to 2,000 counts of mail and wire fraud for manipulating its checking accounts. The company admitted writing checks for amounts exceeding money in the accounts, thereby giving itself interest-free loans. The accounts were replenished before the overdrawn checks cleared, enabling <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> to make extra money by `` riding the float.'' <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, which is now part of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, agreed to pay a $ 2 million fine and reimburse banks that were victims of the check-kiting scheme. Federal investigators said the company had interest-free use of $ 250 million a day. <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON> said the practice was conceived in the late 1970s by <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> management and promoted as a way to get interest-free loans from banks. `` The entire operation was known to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, understood by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, created by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON> said. But `` Mr. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, by his investigation cleared everybody in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a partner in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> law firm of <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Spalding </PERSON>, was retained shortly after the guilty plea was entered by the company. He produced a report three months later that recommended that <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> and eight other branch and regional executives be disciplined. The report exonerated all but one top management official, whom <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> recommended be stripped of any duties involving <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>'s banking activities <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Silbert </PERSON>, said the former attorney general's probe `` was a carefuly, thorough, meticulous and fair and independent investigation.'' <PERSON> Silbert </PERSON> charged that <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> violated company policies limiting overdrafts in order to make extra money. <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> overdrew by as much as 400 percent to take his 10 percent share of interest profits that were given branch managers as an incentive for efficient cash management, <PERSON> Silbert </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> carefully refrained from accusing top managers because there was insufficient evidence they did anything wrong, he said. But <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> and the others named in the report were criticized because `` their conduct was so egregious and abusive and so aggravated and the evidence of proof so overwhelming that he would have been derelict in his responsibility if he had not so named them,'' said <PERSON> Silbert </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney. <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON> said the overdrafting policies were so important to <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>'s business strategy that <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> was admonished when he did not write checks for more than the amounts in the accounts. `` They taught him to overdraft, they told him what branches to use,'' he said. <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s independence was undermined by his relationship to <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, which paid <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Spalding $ 2.5 million to conduct the investigation. `` <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> was supplying the information, <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> was supplying the fee, <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> was controlling the timing of when the report would be released,'' <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a former federal appeals judge who was President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s first attorney general, was paid at a rate of $ 1,711 an hour for 518 hours of work <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> also sued <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, but a federal appeals court ruled that his claim against the brokerage firm must first be submitted to arbitration by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>.
