<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fourteen school and church groups are giving their imprimatur to a new pamphlet that lays out constitutional ways for public schools to teach about religion in a way that does not advocate a particular belief. The sponsors said Tuesday that endorsement of the document by such diverse groups as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelicals </ORGANIZATION> and the research arm of <ORGANIZATION> Americans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Separation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> indicates that the time is ripe for a resurgence of instruction about religion. `` The question is no longer should we teach about religion,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Americans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> told a news conference. `` The question is how do we do this?'' Other participants called the 1,000-word pamphlet historic and expressed hope it will embolden teachers and principals to give religion its due in history, literature and other classes. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> said it shows `` there is a nobler and better way to deal with religion in public schools than simply to yell at each other and threaten a lawsuit.'' All too often, debates about religion in public schools have degenerated into `` a hog-calling or a shouting match,'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said. Secular and religious groups alike, as well as Secretary of Education <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, have complained in recent years that religion gets short shrift in most American classrooms and textbooks, even in courses that teach about historical events in which religion played a prominent part. Some critics blamed publishers' fear of controversy, while others attribute it to an overreaction by educators to <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings in the 1960s that barred state-sponsored school prayer and Bible reading. The pamphlet provides guidance in question-and-answer form for school boards, teachers and others. The pamphlet, called `` Religion in the Public School Curriculum: Questions and Answers,'' notes that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled unconstitutional a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> law that required schools to teach the Biblical account of creation in science classes. But it said the high court also acknowledged a variety of scientific theories about origins can appropriately be taught in a science class. The pamphlet added, `` Though science instruction may not endorse or promote religious doctrine, the account of creation found in various scriptures may be discussed in a religious studies class or in any course that considers religious explanations for the origin of life.'' The pamphlet gives the following general advice on how to teach about religion: _ `` The school's approach is academic, not devotional.'' _ `` The school may sponsor study about religion, but may not sponsor the practice of religion.'' _ `` The school may educate about all religions, but may not promote or denigrate any religion.'' _ `` The school may inform the student about various beliefs, but should not seek to conform him or her to any particular belief.'' `` Because religion plays a significant role in history and society,'' the pamphlet said, `` study about religion is essential to understanding both the nation and the world. Omission of facts about religion can give students the false impression that the religious life of humankind is insignificant or unimportant.'' `` Failure to understand even the basic symbols, practices and concepts of the various religions makes much of history, literature, art and contemporary life unintelligible.'' The pamphlet recommends `` careful'' handling of religious holidays in the classroom, with information focusing `` on the origin, history and generally agreed-upon meaning of the observances.'' Other sponsors include the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religion </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christians </ORGANIZATION> and Jews, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Curriculum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>.
