<HEAD>Reagan Outrages Indians by Saying America `Humored' Their
Ancestors</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDs: <PERSON> Suzan </PERSON> in 4th graf is correct
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The only American Indian in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> says President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> _ in claiming the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` humored'' native Americans by putting them on reservations _ appears to have learned all he knows on the subject from his old Western movies. `` I only wish the president knew as much about <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> as he seems to know about the Russians,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Nighthorse </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION> who represents the western half of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. `` It's incredible he knows so little.'' <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION>, a Democrat, joined a chorus of Indian groups and others in denouncing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remarks to students at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. `` Maybe we made a mistake'' in trying to maintain Indian cultures, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` Maybe we should not have humored them in that, wanting to stay in that kind of primitive lifestyle. Maybe we should have said, ` No, come join us. Be citizens along with the rest of us.''' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> misspoke. All American Indians were made full <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens by an act of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1924. <PERSON> Suzan </PERSON> <PERSON> Harjo </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>, said she found the remark about `` humoring'' the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> `` particularly insulting.'' <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON>, president of the Denver-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I'm a fan of the president, but the president is a little bit removed from the reality of American Indians.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> volunteered his comments when he was asked by a student if he would meet with three Indians visiting <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> under the auspices of the militant <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>. They went to the summit city to call attention to the problems of American Indians. `` We have provided millions of acres of land for what are called preservations _ or the reservations, I should say,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` They, from the beginning, announced that they wanted to maintain their way of life, as they had always lived there in the desert and the plains and so forth. And we set up these reservations so they could, and have a <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> to help take care of them.'' Though many Indians leave the reservations, many stay, the president noted. The 1980 census found 1.37 million Indians, among whom 332,000 were living on 260 reservations. `` We've done everything we can to meet their demands as to what they _ how they want to live,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said, `` He appears not to know that Indians are citizens. `` He must have been learning from these old celluloid Westerns of the 1930s he used to act in,'' the congressman said. `` There's no question that <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> do n't want to lose their traditions. But I do n't know any Indians who want to be primitive.'' <PERSON> Harjo </PERSON> said, `` I thought his notion of having granted Indians millions of acres of land was astonishing ... There was no grant involved; his ancestors were n't dragging any land behind them when they came to this country. `` He has headed the worst administration for <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> since the days of outright warfare and extermination,'' she said, because of `` consistent efforts by this administration to undo legal, long-standing rights and wipe out programs that meet our needs.'' Indians leave reservations for better jobs and education `` and politics,'' <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> said. `` Life can be very hard on a reservation if you're part of the ` Out' party.'' But, `` Many Indians do n't have the choice to move off the reservation'' because they have no job skills that mainstream society will pay for, <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> said. American Indians are among the poorest, worst-off of Americans. A government study noted that the 1980 census found 12 percent of all Americans living in poverty, but poverty among Indians affected 22 percent of those living off the reservation and 41 percent of Indians living on reservations. Unemployment on reservations frequently exceeds 60 percent and can reach 80 percent. Young Indian adults commit suicide at a rate six times their counterparts in mainstream society. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> noted that government policy had tried to dissolve tribes and force Indians to join mainstream culture as small farmers in 1887-1934, then turned around and tried to maintain tribes and tribal governments, but then flipped again to `` termination'' of tribes in the <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> administration in the 1950s and flopped back to `` government-to-government'' policy in subsequent administrations, a policy <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has affirmed. As for AIM and its three members in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> said, `` People in AIM do not speak for all Indians. They speak for only a small minority.''
