<HEAD>Fumes Overcome 38 After Acid Leak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NILES, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Noxious fumes from an acid leak at a factory forced an evacuation of more than 130 residents and sent at least 38 people to a hospital for treatment, authorities said. Many of those treated at <LOCATION> Pawating </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> were players and spectators at softball fields near the National-Standard wire and cable plant where the leak occurred about 6:15 p.m. Tuesday, nursing supervisor <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said. Hydrochloric acid and another acid were mixed in a storage tank, causing the tank to rupture and the acids to form a puddle on the plant floor, said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON>, a dispatcher with the <ORGANIZATION> Berrien </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The leak was contained with no fire or explosion, he said. Residents within three miles of the plant on <PERSON> Niles </PERSON>'s northeast side were ordered evacuated, but they returned when the area was declared safe within three hours, Mayor <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Clymer </PERSON> said. At least 130 people were sheltered temporarily at <ORGANIZATION> Ballard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, about six miles from the plant on the west side of the southwestern <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> city of 15,000, school Superintendent <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Huffman </PERSON> said.
