<HEAD>Washington Wire: A Miracle _ Ronald Reagan Puts Danish Ham on Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sunny skies, a warm breeze, temperatures around 80 and the lilacs in full bloom: <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> could hardly be lovelier. And <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has made it nicer than usual for Muscovites. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s legendary good luck and a crash cleanup by Soviet work crews combined to put the prettiest possible face on this otherwise seedy capital for the superpower summit. Even the city's notorious `` pookh,'' the cotton-wool summer scourge that falls from the city's silver poplar trees, fills the air and covers the ground like snow, has cooperated. It is having either a late season or a light one. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Somov </PERSON>, an architect and would-be artist, was displaying his favorite painting on a downtown street when three Americans approached. One asked how much he'd take for his painting, a stylized Russian Orthodox church scene. When he discovered their nationality, however, he insisted he could n't sell his favorite work but wanted to give it to the American president. `` To Mr. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, with profound respect,'' he wrote on the back, and signed his name. The painting found its way to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s White House staff It was typical of the outpouring of goodwill that has greeted the swarm of Americans and other foreigners, mostly journalists, who have descended on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for the meetings between Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. A 25-year-old woman standing at the edge of Red Square who identified herself as <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> streets `` look prettier because they cleaned everything up for this summit.'' `` If only it would stay this way,'' she said. It wo n't, although the constant hosing down and sweeping of the streets is not extraordinary here. Street sweepers are undeterred even by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s frequent rainy days, but poor grading and practically nonexistent drainage ensure that the streets have almost perpetual puddles in summer. Dirt becomes mud only to be redistributed by the next storm or water truck. Some Americans, particularly those who visited <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> when relations were more strained and its people more suspicious of foreigners, have been surprised by Muscovites approaching them on the street just to practice their English or exchange pleasantries. On the Arbat, the pedestrian mall in the restored historic district that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> visited shortly after arriving Sunday, one artist displayed a mural depicting familiar <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> monuments, and in the middle was a cherubic babe holding <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> flags. The artist, who called himself <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Britikov-Cambridge </PERSON>, told a reporter: `` <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> is one of us. He's an artist.'' But if the summit has brought out a friendly comraderie in a society where people often pass on the street without acknowledging each other, it also has meant some inconvenience. Authorities announced before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> arrived that people without residence permits would not be allowed to come into the city this week, effectively banning an estimated 3 million visitors from outside the capital who crowd in on any given day to stay with relatives, shop, sell home-produced goods or search for hard-to-find commodities. Permanent residents who live near summit sites have been pleased to discover rarely found goods on store shelves that have been barren most of the winter. One shopper refused to believe that an ordinary shop was selling Danish canned ham, a rarity in the best of times, even in the hard-currency berioska stores set up for foreigners. Cars without <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> plates and those that police inspectors fear might break down and clutter the streets have been stopped at roadblocks set up at the city limits. But if the stringent controls have cut down on traffic volume, the extraordinary enthusiasm of the foot police assigned to seal off much of the city center has snarled the remaining traffic in a city which hardly has enough cars to stage a respectable rush hour. More than one driver has exercised his newfound freedom of expression to give policemen a candid opinion of a system that leads innocent motorists into a trap where all vehicles, trucks and buses included, must stop and turn around in the street to escape horrendous tieups. A <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> taxi driver who spent 20 minutes to drive less than three miles grumbled to his American passenger, `` Your president comes, and then when I want to go this way, I have to go the opposite way instead.''
</TEXT>
