t us?'' But the man in his 40s who gave his name only as <PERSON> Vassily </PERSON> is an exception. Most Soviets spoke wistfully of the high-water marks in U.S.-Soviet relations _ the wartime alliance against <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the Soyuz-Apollo flight, the detente of the 1970s. Mrs. <PERSON> Sovelyova </PERSON> was among them. A guide at the monument to the World War II battle of <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION>, now called <LOCATION> Volgograd </LOCATION>, she gestured to the stone pillars that commemorate the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers who died in battle. `` We were once in a common cause,'' she said. `` Let us work together to reinforce peace on our beautiful green planet.''
