 <PERSON> Baskin-Robbins </PERSON> is coming to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, vice president of the <LOCATION> Glendale </LOCATION>, Calif.-based ice cream manufacturer, said Tuesday the company has signed a franchise agreement to sell its 31 flavors at the Hote Rossiya, across from the Kremlin. The Soviets will operate the concession with Baskin-Robbins providing the equipment and the ingredients, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. The store is scheduled to open July 1, about a month after hordes of Americans who were here for the summit leave. Most Soviet citizens, who are frequently seen licking ice cream brought from street vendors, probably will not be able to buy the product at first because it will be sold only for hard currency. But <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the company eventually hopes to work out an arrangement to sell the ice cream for rubbles.
