<HEAD>Seized Research Ship Allowed to Sail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The research ship Atlantis II, seized under the federal zero-tolerance drug policy, was allowed to set sail for <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> but must keep authorities posted on its whereabouts. The ship, which took part in the exploration of the wreck of the Titanic, left its moorage here Tuesday, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Atlantis II remains under `` constructive seizure,'' which means that ship officials must report the craft's position to customs officials at least once a week, said Capt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiljean </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chiljean </PERSON>, who was not the captain when the seizure took place, said Monday the release of the 210-foot vessel was based in part on an agreement that `` this would never happen again.'' The ship, worth an estimated $ 30 million, is now bound for exploration off the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> coast. The stop in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> was a planned one for overhaul of equipment, <PERSON> Chiljean </PERSON> said, and the ship remains on schedule. Customs officials seized Atlantis II on May 18 after finding a tiny bit of marijuana and some residue in a pipe owned by a crew member. The ship was returning with a <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanography </ORGANIZATION> vessel from an exploration off the coast of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The seizure was one of the most publicized of the zero-tolerance program, a federal crackdown in which officials are confiscating boats or vehicles for discovery of any amount of drugs. Protest of the policy, including a congressional attack on it last week, led to a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> decision to use more discretion in deciding whether to seize vessels. Ships outside the 12-mile territorial limit will be taken only if intent to smuggle is determined.
