<HEAD>Japan's Average Household Earns $40,000 Annual Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s average household income has topped $ 40,000 a year, but nearly half of all households report difficulties in making ends meet, according to a survey released today. The nationwide survey conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> showed the average income of Japanese households was $ 40,400 in 1986. The figure was 2.5 percent higher than the previous year, but was the lowest increase since the first such survey was conducted in 1962. The survey, conducted last summer, says there are 38.06 million households in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, with an average 3.19 persons per household. Of the total households, 3.47 million were composed of people 65 years or older, up 4.5 percent from the year before. The survey saysd 43.1 percent of the households of people 65 or older are totally dependent on annuities or pensions. In the survey, 45,000 households, chosen at random, were asked about the ages of their family members, and 8,000 about income. Asked about living standards, 52.4 percent said they were living an `` average'' life, up from 49.7 percent the previous year. Forty percent, unchanged from last year's survey, reported they found it hard to make ends meet. Those who said they were living a `` comfortable'' life accounted for 7.1 percent, down from 9.4 percent. Results of the survey are used in planning the government's future welfare policy
