<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSAntibodies     06-01 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Antibodies,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers: AIDS Virus May Enter Dormant Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE LAYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers have discovered that the AIDS virus apparently may become dormant in the human body and undetectable by the standard test, but say the finding does not mean the nation's blood supply is endangered `` The blood supply is exceptionally safe and protected to a great extent by existing screning tests and the self-deferral of individuals at high risk,'' said <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Polk </PERSON>, a professor of epidemiology at the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and co-author of the study published today in June's Annals of Internal Medicine. Tests to pinpoint the disease and protect blood supplies are based on detection of HIV-1 antibodies, produced naturally by the body to fight the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus. The instances of AIDS victims who stop producing detectable antibodies to the disease appear to be rare and so far have only been observed in those who have shown small amounts of the virus in their bodies, said <PERSON> Homayoon </PERSON> <PERSON> Farzadegan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Saah </PERSON>, also professors of epidemiology at <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> and authors of the study. <PERSON> Farzadegan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Saah </PERSON> said at a news conference Tuesday that four homosexual men infected with AIDS stopped producing detectable antibodies, though a newer test showed they still are infected with the virus. <PERSON> Farzadegan </PERSON> said the phenomenon may mean that the virus has the potential of going into a latent phase, during which it does not reproduce. The four were among 1,000 homosexual men infected with the virus who participated in the continuing study. The four showed the loss of antibodies up to 3 -LCB- years ago, though one has since shown signs of the AIDS infection and has developed antibodies again. `` Usually when an infected person loses HIV-1 antibodies, he or she is in the end stages of AIDS and has a deteriorated immune system,'' said Polk. The four `` had no clinical symptoms of illness, such as swollen lymph glands or abnormal counts of the white blood cells targeted by the virus.'' The researchers reported their findings last June, but could not determine whether the men had been properly diagnosed as having AIDS or whether mistakes had been made in laboratory tests. During the follow-up study, the researchers used a new method to test for the virus instead of the antibody test and determined that the men showed evidence of infection, but not HIV-1 antibodies. The new test, called PCR or polymerase chain reaction assay, magnifies the presence of the virus' genetic material inside cells up to 1 million times. `` We do n't know if something in the virus itself is defective and causing it not to reproduce, or whether it is something within the host,'' Saah said, adding that researchers have not determined whether the disease is transmittable during this phase. <PERSON> Farzadegan </PERSON> said the new test was not commonly used to screen blood donors because of the complexity of conducting it and interpreting its results. In an editorial accompanying the article, Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuck </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said that even though the four would not have been picked out by the AIDS test used by blood centers, the finding does not mean that the blood supply is threatened. He wrote that there was no evidence that unexpectedly large numbers of AIDS virus infections had been spread by transfusions since 1985, when screening began, and that efforts to discourage blood donations from those at high risk for AIDS were largely successful. AIDS attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancers. It is most often transmitted by exposure to the body fluids of a person who carries the disease, including sexual contact, blood transfusions or the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles. All of the men who participated in the initial report are participants in the Multicenter AIDS Cohort Study, which follows nearly 5,000 homosexual and bisexual men in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> to document the natural progression of AIDS.
</TEXT>
