<HEAD>Beach Ban Not Enforced As Summer Season Starts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLS, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The beach season's start brought an onslaught of sunbathers to one of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>'s few sandy beaches but none of the turmoil expected from a ruling that limited access to the seashore in accordance with 17th century Puritan law. But an attorney for homeowners along the cherished beach in southern <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> warned Tuesday that vacationers who relax on the wrong patch of sand could wind up in court. At issue is mile-long <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION>, which a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge ruled in September is in effect private. The judge agreed with 30 homeowners that the beach between the high and low tide marks is limited to fishing, bird hunting and boating based on a 1648 ordinance. The homeowners argued that sunbathers occupy the beach in front of their homes _ property which they say is deeded to them _ and make noise and leave behind trash. Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodrick </PERSON>'s decision has been appealed to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which is expected to rule in September. The high court's decision also could affect some of the remaining 35 miles of sandy beaches along <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>'s 3,500 miles of coastline. Meantime, <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> police Chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Zackular </PERSON> says he will make no trespassing arrests at the beach this summer. He said he was instructed by the offices of the <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> district attorney and state attorney general to withhold enforcing the court decision until the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rules. But <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thaxter </PERSON>, an attorney for the homeowners, believes the town