<HEAD>Clergymen Urge Non-Violent Resistance To Apartheid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of South African clergymen has pledged to organize anti-government protests and called for increased non-violent resistance to apartheid in apparent violation of government restrictions. The decision was made at an emergency conference _ the largest and most broadly based of its type _ that ended Tuesday with a church service at the <ORGANIZATION> Regina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mundi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s largest black township. `` We are determined we are going to obey God whatever the cost,'' Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> told a mostly-black crowd of 1,200 during the service. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> then ripped symbolic gags from the mouths of black and white youths on the podium, took up a wooden cross and carried it back and forth down the cathedral's center aisle. The audience sang an African hymn, then held hands and swayed together, singing the American civil rights song, `` We Shall Overcome.'' Security force vehicles, including a tear-gas truck, lined the street outside. More than 200 religious leaders representing more than 30 church groups assembled Monday in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> to consider new tactics to oppose the white minority government's racial policies. They ended the two-day convocation with a decision to mobilize support for a three-day national protest planned next week by black trade unions. They also said that, on June 12, they would start a campaign for the release of political prisoners. The campaign is to end July 18th _ the 70th birthday of jailed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>. The Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Af