 mandating segregated residential areas. The convocation was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, which includes major Protestant denominations active in the fight for black rights. Also participating were the Roman Catholic Church and a number of independent African churches. Organizers said political conditions in the country have worsened since leading clergymen decided in early February to organize the convocation. They cited the effective bannings of 17 anti-apartheid organizations, the closure of two opposition newspapers and pending legislation to restrict labor unions and opposition political groups.
