<HEAD>Dollar Gains, Stocks Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained ground against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today, while stock prices surged following an overnight advance on Wall Street. After opening higher at 125.23 yen, the dollar climbed further, closing at 125.35 yen, up a strong 0.55 yen from Tuesday's finish. `` The dollar held steady between 125.10 and 125.37 yen throughout the day in mixed trading,'' said a foreign exchange dealer with a major <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. There were active selling orders from export-related industries but the dollar was supported by buying by financial organizations, he said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which gained 193.60 points Tuesday, added another 287.21 points, or 1.04 percent, closing the day's trading at 27,703.91. Share prices rose almost across the board, encouraged by Tuesday's rise on <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, where the Dow Jones industrial average gained 74.68 points and rose about the 2,000-point level, traders said. Wall Street's rally prompted <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> investors to erase their worries about the possibility of a hike in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> discount rate, an analyst said, speaking on condition of anonymity. Volume on the first section was estimated at a heavy 2.5 billion shares, up from 1.7 billion shares on Tuesday. It was the heaviest volume this year, and near the market's record of 2.83 billion shares set in March last year. Prominent among winners were steels, constructions and chemicals. Drugs, electricals and automobiles also gained ground.
