<HEAD>Ethiopian Leader Denies State Is Using Food As A Weapon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Mengistu promising to allow more U.N.
personnel into the north to ensure flow of aid, INSERT two grafs
after 12th graf, `Mengistu ... against us.'' Picks up 13th graf
pvs, ` Rebels of ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON> denies his government is using food as a weapon in northern provinces where secessionist insurgencies and crop failures threaten the lives of 3.2 million people. For the first time, the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> leader also accused Arab countries of backing the rebel movement. He claimed the Moslem nations want to consolidate their control of the Red Sea. During Tuesday's six-hour news conference, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION>'s first with foreign reporters in two years, he also called for better relations with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The moustachioed Marxist leader spoke with unprecedented candor on numerous other issues, gesticulating with passion, occasionally smiling and laughing. <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> denied his government is using food as a weapon in the north, where the war and a government counteroffensive have jeopardized a massive Western-financed relief effort for millions of people facing starvation in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and Tigre provinces. `` How is it possible, how is it imaginable that a government which came to power by the will of the people ... can be accused of using food as a weapon,'' <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We revolutionaries do not live for ourselves, we live for others.'' In early April, the government ordered all foreign relief workers out of <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and Tigre for security reasons. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> at first said it was defying the order to recall its 25 or so workers, citing a `` humanitarian responsibility for the fate of some 5 million people'' in the two drought-stricken provinces. When the government insisted that the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> workers leave the areas, the agency locked up its supplies and trucks and left. On May 22, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> gave the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> 15 days to hand over the food. <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> officials denied earlier requests because they said they must be present to supervise the food's distribution. In the past, there have been allegations that food destined for starving farmers has fed Ethiopian troops. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said the rebels are using the food issue `` to elicit international sympathy and support for them to promote their propaganda activities against us.'' On Sunday, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> had promised when the two met two days earlier to allow the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to expand its role in the north to ensure the continued flow of aid. The chief <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> representative in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Priestley </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> had promised `` in principle'' to allow more <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> personnel into the north and to permit them to move outside government-held towns. Rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> have been fighting for 27 years in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s oldest civil war and have won major victories this year with the capture of several towns. <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON>, who is in his mid-40s, made no reference to a younger insurgency by rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Tigrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, who have been fighting for 14 years. During the conference, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said unspecified Arab nations were backing the Eritrean group. Rebels `` have embarked on a project of convincing the Arab world of an alleged oppression of the Moslems in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> in order to invoke the sympathy of the Arabs,'' he said. He said Arabs were helping the rebels in order to `` keep <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> from the riches of the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s ports of <LOCATION> Assab </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massawa </LOCATION>, both in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, are the only Red Sea ports not controlled by <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states. <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> would be landlocked without them. In the past, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> has always said Western nations supported the rebel movement. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said the rebels also had won support from leftist countries, which diplomats identified as <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. About 2,500 Cuban troops stationed in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> have refused to fight in the north. <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> defended his country's Marxist revolution of September 1974, calling it `` human and democratic'' and claiming it had improved the lives of the country's 42 million people. He warned that relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be hurt if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> decides to stop annual imports of 20,000 tons of Ethiopian coffee, a move it is debating. Still, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said he hopes for better ties with <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>: `` We have always pushed for better relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and I hope the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will reciprocate ... Once upon a time we were good friends.'' Western diplomats were puzzled by <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION>'s conciliatory attitude. They pointed out that <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> at the last minute caused <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> affairs, to cancel a visit in January when <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> announced he would not be meeting <LOCATION> Mengistu </LOCATION>. In February, <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> said he believed <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> was not serious about improving relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Once-warm <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with this East African country deteriorated after the 1974 revolution in which <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> and a clique of fellow army officers overthrew Emperor <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continued to arm the new military government until <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> in 1977. In a dramatic superpower flip-flop, the Soviets started backing <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> switched to <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>.
