 City </LOCATION>.'' Until now, abusive students were suspended or transferred to other schools. The city was researching whether it needs action by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to permit expulsions, the mayor said. The recent outbreak of school violence included a baseball-bat attack on one teacher and another who was burned when she picked up a huge firecracker tossed into her classroom. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabrino </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said that from last July 1 to April 30, there were 969 reported assaults in the city's schools, 198 on teachers. The police patrols will be instituted at the 200 schools with the highest number of serious incidents, officials said. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said metal detectors will be put in some schools on a test basis and identification cards will be issued for everyone in the school system. In addition, electromagnetic locks will be installed so that a signal will sound when outside school doors are left open, and teachers will be able to push a button in the classroom that will let the security office listen in.
