<HEAD>Pilot Says His Soviet Flyover Not A Political Statement, But A
Mistake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to CLARIFY that Summer passed into Soviet
territory on Saturday and Sunday. PICKS up 9th graf pvs, ```The
weather ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German pilot says bad weather caused him to fly his small plane over Soviet territory over the weekend and that his jaunt into Russian airspace was a mistake, not a political statement. <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Sommer </PERSON> said he blundered across the border in bad weather Saturday in a single-engine <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> 150 and did it again on Sunday. <PERSON> Sommer </PERSON> said he did n't know that Saturday marked the first anniversary of a flight by <PERSON> Mathias </PERSON> <PERSON> Rust </PERSON>, who stunned the world by flying a light plane through Soviet air defenses to Red Square. Rust now is serving a four-year prison term in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sommer </PERSON>'s flight caused a diplomatic flurry, particularly because of suspicions the incursion had something to do with the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. He said he hopes the summit `` brings peace and detente,'' but his vacation flight had nothing to do with it. In <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Lasse </PERSON> <PERSON> Seim </PERSON> said the plane crossed the Soviet border while on a 100-mile flight from <LOCATION> Ivalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Kirkenes </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s Barents Sea coast. He said it went deeper into <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> territory when it returned to <LOCATION> Ivalo </LOCATION> on Sunday, staying in Soviet airspace for as long as 30 minutes. <PERSON> Sommer </PERSON>, a part-time <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> bus driver with 23 years as an amateur pilot, said he passed into Soviet territory both days while flying in a cloud cover at 1,000 feet. He said he said he first learned that he had strayed into Soviet territory on Sun