<HEAD>Pregnant Women Given Dilantin Without Consent During Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Up to 240 pregnant women were given a drug linked to birth defects without their knowledge as part of a study, and officals are considering disciplining the researchers. Dilantin, a drug commonly used to treat epilepsy, was given by two <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> anesthesiologists to about 245 pregnant women to determine whether it could reduce fetal stress in Caesarean births, hospital spokesman <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said Tuesday. Five of the women had consented to participate in the hospital-approved study from September 1987 through January, said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, chairman of the hospital's scientific committee. The other women were given the drug without their knowledge and without approval from the hospital's review board, said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who, unlike <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, said he understood that only some of these approximately 240 women were pregnant. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dilantin </PERSON> has been linked to birth defects when administered early in pregnancy. But he said the women received the drug 15 minutes before delivering their babies. The president of the <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the hospital, said he would hold a meeting Monday to discuss punishment for the doctors, who have not been identified. `` I was appalled to think that men in the medical profession would do that,'' board President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` They, of all people, should know that you do n't experiment on patients without obtaining their written consent.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates the licensing of hospitals, is aware of the doctors' action but is barred by state law from revealing whether it is investigating, said spokeswoman Penny Strong. Spokesman <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state's attorney's office declined to comment on whether his office was investigating to see if criminal laws were violated The women all received a single, smaller-than-normal dose of the drug, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. Two of the babies died because of unrelated complications, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. Several studies have reported higher incidences of birth defects, including heart abnormalities and retardation, among babies born to women who use Dilantin and other anti-epileptic drugs. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he did not agree with the doctors' actions but did not consider them unethical. But a medical ethicist called the practice a `` serious abuse'' of the medical profession. `` It seems to me that it simply goes against the principles of biomedical ethics ... -LRB- which -RRB- really require that any person enrolled in a research project be informed of that and be given a chance to consent or refuse,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Childress </PERSON>, a religion and medical education professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>. `` What it amounts to -LRB- is -RRB- ... basically using human beings as means to other ends ... not treating them as ends in themselves,'' he said. `` Even though the risk was limited, it was still a serious abuse.'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said the failure to gain the women's consent was a violation of hospital policy. The hospital's executive medical staff recommended May 18 that the doctors be given probation, a warning that would pave the way for stricter measures if they further violate hospital policy, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. `` An ultimate decision -LRB- on what action is taken against the doctors -RRB- would rest with the board of trustees,'' which is to meet Monday, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said none of the women has sued the hospital.
