<HEAD>Number of Soviet Jewish Dropouts Reaches Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs to UPDATE with figures from Geneva group.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of Soviet Jewish emigrants who decided against coming to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> reached a record high in May, when more than 90 percent chose to settle elsewhere, a Soviet Jewish activist told the Israeli newsagency <ORGANIZATION> Itim </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chessler </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewry </ORGANIZATION>, was quoted as saying Tuesday that soon no Soviet Jewish emigrants will come to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> unless they are flown via <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, instead of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, where they are free to immigrate to other Western countries. Israeli officials are embarrassed by the high dropout figure because of their 20-year-long battle for the right of Soviet Jews to emigrate on the grounds that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is their homeland. Israeli leaders claim 400,000 Soviet Jews want to settle in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. But less than 20 percent of those who leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> actually settle here. <PERSON> Chessler </PERSON> said that of the 1,169 Jews who left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in May, just 110 came to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, a drop of nearly 7 percent from April. Of the 4,695 Soviet Jews who have emigrated so far this year, 18 percent have settled in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, he added. Meanwhile, in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Intergovernmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migration </ORGANIZATION> announced that Jewish emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <L