<HEAD>Gorbachev News Conference At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here at a glance are some of the key points raised by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> during his news conference Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S.-SOVIET RELATIONS AND ARMS CONTROL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> noted that developments have become possible `` due to realism'' but that it is `` not an easy process at all.'' The 24-page document agreed at this meeting lays `` bricks so to say for the building of our future relationship. It is a sign for movement into the 21st century.'' The exchange of ratification documents on the intermediate-range weapons treaty `` turned the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> meeting into a watershed political event in the Soviet-American dialogue and in world politics as a whole.'' Yet he said it is not easy to make progress on strategic arms, calling negotiations on this issue `` the most complex task we confronted in post-war politics.'' `` Step by step, we are moving towards a treaty.'' But he strongly criticized the contrary attitude that he said had led to last-minute difficulties on agreeing the text of the joint statement. `` I believe that we have missed a chance to take an important step forward toward civilized relations,'' he said. He added however, that `` even though not everything has been achieved as we would have wanted it, we will not make any dramatic conclusions.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HUMAN RIGHTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said `` there has been some progress in this sense,'' using wording that suggested resolution of some individual cases. But he strongly criticized what he called `` propaganda gambits'' and `` all sorts of spectacles, all sorts of shows'' in apparent allusion to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s meeting Monday with dissidents and refuseniks. `` I'm not filled with admiration for this part of the visit,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> added. He noted that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had had a chance to get to know Soviet people and emphasized that the president, asked on Tuesday whether he still stuck to his March 1983 view of the <ORGANIZATION> Svoiet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> as an `` evil empire,'' had said he did not. `` He said no and he said this within the walls of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, right in the heart of the evil empire,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` We take note of this.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s `` evil empire'' comment sparked a torrent of vicious comment when it was made, leading to an escalation in Soviet attacks that culminated in comparision between <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> in the deep freeze that followed the shooting down of the Korean Air liner in September 1983 and the breaking off of arms talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in November that year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REGIONAL CONFLICTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 On the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said for the first time that as soon as an international conference on the region is convened, `` we are prepared to address ourselves to regularizing relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' severed in 1967. In general, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said `` real possibilities have appeared for solving regional problems,'' but gave no specifics. He cited the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> agreement as an example of what could be achieved if the superpowers worked together with warring parties to solve the conflicts, but noted that if Soviet forces now come under attack from rebels as they withdraw, `` we shall react accordingly and appropriately. That should be absolutely clear.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JACKSON-VANIK AMENDMENT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 After talking about what he called the contrary attitude of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on some issues, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> singled out economic relations. `` Authoritative parts of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> business circles would like to do business. They are faced with intimidation and all sorts of restrictions,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. Alluding to the Jackson-Vanik amendment, he said, `` There is indeed a most unfavored nation status with regard to the treatment of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' `` Why should the dead drag on the coattails of the living? One is physically dead, the other is politically dead. The amendment was passed in totally different circumstances a decade ago. We should base our policies on present-day realities.'' The amendment, passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1974, requires that any communist nation give assurance of free emigration to be entitled to most-favored-nation trade status.
</TEXT>
