 The first monkey born at a breeding colony started by <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> has begun a three-year stay with a family to help train the animal to assist handicapped people with household tasks. `` We've been waiting two years for this,'' said <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Koehler </PERSON> when Disney World officials Tuesday gave her <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON>, a 6-week-old capuchin monkey. `` I can honestly say it's just like having my first child. It's that exciting.'' Disney started a colony of 63 monkeys in January and hopes to produce 25 monkeys a year for a program called Helping Hands: Simian Aides for the Disabled. By living with <PERSON> Koehler </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON> will learn to trust humans; the Koehlers, in effect, will be <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON>'s foster parents. Then <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON> will go to <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> for six more months of training. The Koehlers are not disabled. Eventually, <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON> will learn to take food from a refrigerator and place it in front of its owner, put a Thermos in a holder, open its lid and put in a straw. The animal will also learn to clean up spills and bring a quadriplegic a mouth stick, which is used to type and turn book pages. The program was started 10 years ago by <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>, a behavioral scientist at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Seven monkeys from other breeding programs have been placed with quadriplegics and 11 more are in training. Nearly 70 more are in foster homes across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
