<HEAD>Gorbachev Threatens Action in Afghanistan, Hints At Mideast
Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> today condemned rebel attacks on Soviet troops withdrawing from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and said it `` should be absolutely clear'' that his forces would respond to any further assaults. He also told a televised news conference at the close of his summit talks with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will consider restoring diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as soon as an international conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> is convened. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> indicated, however, that disagreements over Palestinian representation and other issues still block agreement on calling an international conference. The Kremlin severed relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1967 over <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s six-day war against its Arab neighbors. At separate post-summit news conferences, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> both cited the agreement on a Soviet withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> as an example of how the superpowers can help settle regional conflicts by working with parties that are directly involved. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> noted Afghan rebel attacks on Soviet troops and the embassy in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, including one attack near <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> on Tuesday in which several Soviet soldiers died. If Soviet forces come under attack as they withdraw, `` we shall react accordingly and appropriately,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` That should be absolutely clear.'' A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, speaking only on condition that he not be identified, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> clearly meant that his army would return fire if attacked by Moslem rebels battling the Soviet-backed government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. This official said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> complained to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> during their summit talks about the attacks on withdrawing Soviet troops. At the same time, however, Soviet chief of staff Marshal <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Akhromeyev </PERSON> outlined details of the schedule for withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15. The Soviets recently disclosed that 311 of their soldiers were missing in action there. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students Tuesday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was willing to assist efforts to find the missing troops. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said today that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Pakistani authorities had been contacted and that `` we shall do all we can to return these people to their homes.'' On the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said `` there has been a drawing closer of our positions'' with superpower agreement on the need for an international conference. Problems of Palestinian representation and an agenda are still to be resolved, he said. `` We've given the Americans several years of opportunity to go it alone'' in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` They saw that they could n't.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told reporters that `` real possibilities have appeared for solving regional problems,'' but neither he nor <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> discussed details of their discussions on <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
