<HEAD>Wilbur Jimbob Rogers Won't Be On Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabon </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> wants to run for a seat on a state regulatory agency, he ca n't do it under the name <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimbob </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> dismissed his request for a name change Tuesday because he was leery of `` sanctioning this statewide big political joke.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, an attorney and candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates state utilities and the oil and gas industry, said the judge also expressed concern that the `` intent of it is to be confusing to the voter.'' `` He thought it would be a bad idea for me professionally,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said while his action may help establish `` parameters for buffoonery,'' it was a `` joke that also has a moral. The intent is to kick people in the pants and say, ` Think before you vote.''' In a May 11 court petition, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said he wanted the change `` as a measure of the degree of respect and regard ... for <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>'s political heritage.'' He said he selected <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> in honor of <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, a former state labor commissioner often cited as an example of the political value of a famous name. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> liked Jimbob for its `` basic down-home appeal,'' and thought `` anyone named <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> has always been able to get elected to anything in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>,'' where the humorist <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> was born. He said he would have changed his name back to <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabon </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> after the election.
