<HEAD>Fish, Seal Deaths Blamed On Waste Polluting North Sea Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government minister today called for international action to reduce pollution in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> after thousands of fish and hundreds of seals were reported dead along their shores. Environment Minister <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Toepfer </PERSON> told a special <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> committee meeting that action to reduce the dumping of wastes was needed because of `` strong suspicions'' it threatened sea life. During the meeting, the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Greens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> demanded the government immediately ban ships from getting rid of chemical and other wastes at sea. About 50 dead seals have been found on West German shorelines in the past month, while about 300 have been discovered along <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s coasts, <PERSON> Toepfer </PERSON> said. He said biologists checking the dead seals discovered they were suffering from a virus that caused their deaths. Experts last weekend said pneumonia was the `` final cause'' of death. Thousands of tons of fish meanwhile died from a blanket of yellow sea algae in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Toepfer </PERSON> said. The algae, up to 10 feet thick in some places, spread from the coasts of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and now threatens <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, Danish officials said. West German reports have said the fish were dying from slime from the algae, which coated their gills and prevented them from breathing. Experts blamed nitrates from agricultural fertilizers and phosphorus from sewage and industrial pollution for the dramatic growth of the algae. In <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, fish farmers were advised to kill their fish. Resort owners in western <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> fear news of the algae may ruin the summer tourist season