<HEAD>MOSCOW: a treaty. ...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 I feel that we have now approached a situation where we should note that here too, insofar as the hot trouble spots -LRB- on the -RRB- planet are concerned, real possibilities have appeared for solving these regional problems, for untying _ unraveling these knots _ these tight knots on the basis of political approaches, on the basis of a balance of interests. In substance, we have noted today that first there is <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, then secondly there is the processes concerning the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. There is some joining closer together of positions and a maturing of understanding that there is a need to resolve the problem on the basis of an international conference. ... Then there is the problem of <LOCATION> Campuchia </LOCATION>, thanks to the initiatives taken by <PERSON> Viet </PERSON> <PERSON> Nam </PERSON> and Campuchia of late. That problem too is now becoming one which can be _ which does lend itself to solutions very soon. There are processes under way in <LOCATION> Latin-Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, solutions are possible. ... I have always emphasized and I emphasize this in my conversations with the president, as with all other Americans, we should not _ we must not lose our chance. And in this connection, I said outright to the president that the signing of the agreement on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is a precedent which goes far beyond the limits of that problem alone, because it is the first case, first example, where the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, together with those directly involved in the conflict, signed an agreement which opens up an avenue for a political solution of that problem. ... In questions concerning human rights, humanitarian issues, there has been some progress in this sense. I posed the question in my talks with the president. I said there are facts relating to this sphere, individual cases, which do appear. We've always been giving attentive consideration to them, and we shall continue to do so. ... The more I think over this situation, the more I come to the conclusion that I can see that the American administration does not have a real understanding of the real situation insofar as human rights are concerned. They just do n't know about the processes in the sphere of democracy and democratization in this country. ... So I suggested to the president, let's organize, within the framework of inter-parliamentary exchange, a permanent seminar which would gather together members of our parliaments, representatives of political circles, public circles, and they should then exchange information and assessments. ... The president _ somebody asked the president whether he still considered the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to be an `` evil empire.'' He said no, and he said that within the walls of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, next to the czar's gun, right in the heart of that `` evil empire.'' We take note of that. As the ancient Greeks say, everything flows, everything changes. Everything is in a state of flux. ... Today, when we were able to see that you can not resolve any of the world's problems through military means _ where we came more and more to the conclusion that they have to be resolved politically, by political means on the basis of a balance of interest, on the basis of respect for the social choice. And whether we want to or not, we must all learn to live in peace in this real world of ours. ... And proceeding ... from the fact that there is an understanding _ in fact, that there are lessons which we have drawn from the events in the past years, we suggested, let us then make a statement to that effect _ a joint statement to that effect. Here is the draft that I suggested to the president: `` Both of us proceeding from an awareness of the obtaining realities in the present day world believe that no problems in dispute are insoluble and that they should not be resolved by military means, that peaceful co-existence is something that we resolve as a universal principle of international relations, and that the equality of all states, non-interference in domestic affairs, and freedom of socio-political choice should be recognized as inalienable and mandatory for all.'' I gave the president both the Russian and English text. He read it and he said, `` I like it.'' But when today we met in order to finalize the text of the joint statement it turned out that not everybody likes it among those who surround the president, that kind of a statement. And that's what we were debating this morning. ... We were not able either to agree on the subject of talks on conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. ... Now I'm thinking, there's so much talk that we should not move forward to 50 percent cuts in strategic arms unless we address ourselves to reductions in conventional arms and armaments in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. But as soon as we try to suggest some _ make some real proposals, in order to get that process under way, we immediately come up against some kind of incomprehensible maneuvers and attempts to deviate from that _ from the issue. When everybody voiced concern over the fact that the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> supposedly has a preponderance, we said, `` OK, let's exchange data, let's exchange data.'' The other side immediately tried to dodge the issue. ... The Americans did not accept our bold plan, three-phase plan for eliminating asymmetry and disbalances in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> aimed at building a structure of non-offensive arms and armed forces, with a considerably lower level of arms. We feel that we've missed a good chance to impart some good dynamics, both to relations between the two most powerful military groups, and thereby to promote international security as a whole. ...
</TEXT>
