<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> looking on, a Republican member of a bipartisan deficit-reduction commission said today the panel would not be swayed from doing its job by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s declaration that he would oppose any tax increase Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, R-Minn., said he thought such comments were premature <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, who is here at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s vacation retreat for the second of two days of talks on economic issues, told reporters, `` We are not going to get involved in any presidential campaigns.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the all-but-certain Republican presidential nominee, said Tuesday that he would ignore what he said was a likely recommendation from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for a tax increase to reduce the budget deficit. During a picture-taking session today on the porch of the vice president's seaside home, <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON> was asked if he felt <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s remarks would inhibit his own work on the commission `` I took an oath to work on the commission and to do it well,'' <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON> said. At that point, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> interrupted, saying, `` I hope the commission will listen a little bit to the American people in this election. I think that's what an election is all about. The commission can take an objective look at -LRB- taxes -RRB- and do whatever it wants. But I'd be more persuaded by what Americans say.'' Former deputy <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, one of a half-dozen private economists here for the talks, said taxes were `` off the table and nobody has raised it yet.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was asked to comment on Democratic charges that his call for closing the budget deficit with a modified freeze on spending and with no new taxes was not realistic. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` It is not surprising the Democrats would say that. All they want to do is spend and tax. There is no change I can see or hear out on the campaign that would lead you to believe anything other than that on the Democratic side.'' One day earlier, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who touts himself as a would-be `` education president,'' said local taxes may have to go up if his call for better schools is heeded. `` They may have to,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` Ninety-three percent of the money for education comes from sources other than the federal government. If it's taxes, that's where it has to be.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s comments came as he repeated his oft-stated opposition to a federal tax increase. `` I've pledged no tax increase and I'm going to stay with it, period,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The vice president, speaking after meeting with a group of private economists, also cautioned the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> against clamping down too tightly on credit in the name of fighting inflation. `` I'm not hypercritical of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, but I do n't want to see action taken that's going to shut down economic growth in this country,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The deficit-reduction panel, formed earlier this year, plans to submit its recommendations to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 21. In addition to members appointed by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and by both parties in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the panel will have two members named by whoever wins the election in November. `` It seems to me that the commission might well come up with a tax increase. And I'll be saying, ` Wait a minute. I've taken my case to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people to hold the line on taxes.''' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed eliminating the budget deficit with what he calls a `` flexible freeze'' on spending. All programs, except Social Security benefits, would be held at 1989 levels plus inflation. Increases in one area would have to be offset by decreases in another. The vice president holds a second day of talks today with the same group of economic advisers. Among them is <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> economist who quit his job as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s chief economist in 1985 when his advocacy of a tax increase to reduce the budget deficit ran afoul of the administration's stance against general tax increases. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that during his meeting Tuesday with the economic advisers, `` there was an expression of hoping that <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy would not be too tight.'' `` I think watching for signs of inflation is fine,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` But as a word of caution, I would n't want to see them step over some boundary that would ratchet down, tighten down, the economic growth.'' The nation is in its 65th month of economic expansion, a peacetime record. An economic downturn before the election could spell big troubles for Republicans' election prospects, most economic and political consultants agree. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign has been having some economic problems of its own lately _ a shortage of cash. Two months ago, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides reported that they only had $ 4 million left to spend before the Republican convention. Aide <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Teeter </PERSON> said Tuesday that the amount has now dwindled to just under $ 1.5 million. The vice president said over the weekend that the squeeze may mean some curtailing of campaign travel in the weeks ahead. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign has had no trouble raising money, but it is close to bumping up against the pre-convention federal spending limit of $ 27 million. The campaign has raised $ 29.5 million, of which about $ 2.5 is not subject to the ceiling.
