<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Shrine     06-01 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Shrine,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Deification of Slain Soldier Was Constitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s armed forces did not violate the Constitution when a slain soldier was made a Shinto god against the wishes of his Christian widow, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled Wednesday. <PERSON> Yasuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON> lost a 15-year battle when the nation's highest court reversed lower court decisions upholding her complaint. She said the Self Defense Forces had violated her constitutional freedom of religion by deifying her husband at a Shinto shrine. Her husband, 1st Lt. <PERSON> Takafumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON>, was killed in a traffic accident while serving in the Ground Self Defense Forces in January 1968. Mrs. <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON>, then 34 and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, laid her husband's ashes to rest at <ORGANIZATION> Shinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Yamaguchi </LOCATION>. He was not a Christian. Four years after his death, <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON> was enshrined and deified. His widow filed her suit the next year, in 1973. In her legal action, the first individual lawsuit contesting the government on an issue involving religion, Mrs. <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON> also sought $ 8,000 in compensation from the government for her mental anguish. `` I have long suspected that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was an institution obsequious to the powerful. Today, I'm sorry to see that the court is,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON> told reporters after the decision. <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>, leader of the major opposition <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, told the same news conference: `` I would call the ruling a compromise by the guardian of the constitution made in favor of the government's way of thinking. `` I feel like we're being driven back to the past,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON> has said she filed the suit to challenge the possible revival of the militarism that revolved around <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s traditional Shintoism before and during World War II Before 1945, soldiers killed in action or while on duty were automatically given the status of gods and their names were inscribed in Shinto shrines. The practice was discontinued under the new constitution, which guarantees freedom of religion and was written under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> guidance after <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s defeat. But soldiers killed on duty are sometimes enshrined at the request of the association of retired <ORGANIZATION> Self </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> members, called `` taiyukai.'' In its 14-1 vote Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the armed forces were not directly involved in the case of Lt. <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON> and that the `` taiyukai'' had him enshrined. The lower courts had ruled that the armed forces had a direct role in the enshrinement. Shintoism is said to have emerged at the dawn of Japanese history and crystalized as a religious system during the <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION> period in the eighth century. As the state religion before 1945, it stressed the divinity of the emperor and the worship of nature, ancestors and ancient heroes. The military used Shinto shrines and ceremonies to promote nationalism among the Japanese. The Rev. <PERSON> Mototsugu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogata </PERSON>, chief guardian of the <LOCATION> Gokoku </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shrine </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Yamaguchi </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview, `` Lt. <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON> is one of a total of 52,099 enshrined in a big, tall sacred mirror at this shrine ... established in 1941. They are mostly those killed in World War II.'' Like the others, <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON>'s name has been written in a sacred list as `` mikoto <PERSON> Takafumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakaya </PERSON>,'' said the Shinto priest. `` Mikoto'' is the Shinto term for god or deity. The religion respects several types of deities, including ancestral gods, gods revered for virtues, gods revered for their works and gods whose wrath is to be feared. Shintoism, a religion of ceremony rather than dogma, coexists in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with Buddhism, the other major religion. The exact number of adherents is not known, and many Japanese practice both religions. There are also about 1 million Christians among the 122 million Japanese.
