<HEAD>Police Say Rapists and Killers Among Rebels Seeking Amnesty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rapists, killers and robbers were among 113 rebels who surrendered under an amnesty that guarantees immunity from prosecution, police said Wednesday. Officials said the amnesty was a success and they believe virtually all the rebels turned themselves in by the deadline at midnight Tuesday. `` I can not think of any dissidents still remaining in the <PERSON> bush </PERSON>,'' Wednesday's <ORGANIZATION> Harare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> newspaper quoted Home Minister <PERSON> Moven </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahachi </PERSON> as saying. <PERSON> Mahachi </PERSON> said intelligence estimates were that 100 to 120 rebels were at large before President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> announced the amnesty April 19. Among those granted amnesty is <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sango </PERSON>, who was <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>'s most wanted man and called himself <PERSON> Gayigusu </PERSON> _ `` Grind the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'' in the Ndebele language <PERSON> Sango </PERSON>, in his 30s, fought as a guerrilla in the seven-year war that transformed the white-governed British colony of <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION> into black-governed <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> on April 18, 1980. He deserted from the army in 1982 after <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON> <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>, the former opposition leader, was fired from a coalition government for allegedly plotting a coup against <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>. Most of the rebels were loyal to <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, whose power base is the minority <PERSON> Ndebele </PERSON> tribe. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s ruling <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is strongest in his dominant <PERSON> Shona </PERSON> tribe. As a dissident gang leader roaming the rolling <PERSON> bush </PERSON> country of <LOCATION> Matabeleland </LOCATION> province in western <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, the Ndebele homeland, <PERSON> Sango </PERSON> was blamed for a wave of murder, robbery and rape. He is alleged to have led the gang that axed 16 white missionaries and family members to death six months ago, including five children and five women, on two Pentecostal communal farms near <LOCATION> Bulawayo </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Matabeleland </LOCATION> provincial capital. Like the others who surrendered under the amnesty, <PERSON> Sango </PERSON> is immune from prosecution that almost certainly would have cost him his life. The government has promised a rehabilitation program to ease them bak into society. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> offered the amnesty, the first since independence, after he and <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> signed an agreement Dec. 23 to merge their political parties. An amnesty <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> offered under a cease-fire before independence was accepted by about 50,000 guerrillas loyal to either <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, some of whom were among the 113 who turned themselves in this time. `` Smelling Blood'' <PERSON> Mavovonka </PERSON> led the last gang of 12 men to surrender hours before the deadline. He told reporters in the <LOCATION> Nkayi </LOCATION> district of northern <LOCATION> Matabeleland </LOCATION>: `` We went out to the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> because of misunderstandings. Our leaders have now seen that what they were doing was wrong and they have corrected their mistakes. That's why we are here.'' <PERSON> Mahachi </PERSON>, the home minister, said last week the amnesty would not be extended and rebels refusing it would be hunted down and killed. `` I am sure the amnesty is 100 percent successful,'' he said Tuesday. `` There may be one or two or three still outstanding. The problem is that we were not certain of the total number, but the number which we have received is about what we expected it to be.''
