<HEAD>MOSCOW: a whole. ...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Before concluding my statement, let me just share with you one general impression _ and if I did not mention this, I would not be honest with you or truthful, if I omitted to say this: It is my impression ... there is a lot of contradictions in the American position. ... Now, let me explain where I see this contrariness. On the one hand, we have a joint statement that there should be no war, that war is inadmissible, we are engaged in a businesslike dialogue about arms reductions, we're talking about preferences for political solutions. And yet, on the other hand, we keep hearing ... _ we heard words about a stake made on strength. ... This is to be seen in the economic ties also, where an authoritative part _ sections of the American business circles are in favor of cooperation, but they are faced with intimidation with all sorts of restrictions. There is indeed a most unfavored nation treatment in respect to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. We had a very intense discussion with the president yesterday on this subject. And I asked, `` Why should the dead hold onto the coattails of the living?'' I mean the Jackson-Vanik Amendment. One of them's already physically dead. The other's politically dead. `` Why should they hang onto our coattails?'' I asked. This was _ the amendment was passed in a totally different situation a decade ago, but in this changed world of ours, we should think and base our policies on present day realities. ... Q. You mentioned twice in your comments just a few moments ago, you talked about missing chances, and you have also talked about politics is the art of the possible. So I ask you with this administration and its president, is it going to be possible to have a treaty, to have a START -LRB- strategic arms reduction -RRB- treaty, if the Americans insist on keeping the SDI -LRB- strategic defense initiative -RRB- program going? GORBACHEV: I am sure that there still is a possibility to achieve a treaty this year and I'm reinforced in this optimism by the headway we have made _ <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> have made in this past period _ and also the exchange of views here almost around the clock. It gives me grounds to voice such an optimistic assessment. ... Q. Mr. General Secretary, several times in the past few days you were asked if there would be a fifth summit conference with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> possible in the fall, and you answered usually, `` Yes, it is possible, it is possible, but it depends on how things go at this meeting.'' Now that this meeting is about over, do you see enough headway _ progress _ to warrant a fifth meeting with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in the fall? GORBACHEV: I link the possibility to arrive at a treaty, and therefore, I believe, that a fifth meeting is also possible, and that possibility is still at the very real. So, the whole thing hinges upon that one question. ... Q. The Arab countries highly assess your recent words about the Palestinians who are now waging a courageous struggle against the Israeli occupiers. Would you tell me what you achieved in your meetings with Mr. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on the <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> issue and on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> settlement as a whole? GORBACHEV: ... There is an understanding among the international community and in the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> among its permanent members that the solution should be solved along the lines of an international conference. The content of that conference has not yet been determined though. ... We can not decide for the Arabs, how the Palestinians participate in the international conference. Let them decide for themselves, let the Arabs decide. What we should do, the Americans and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, we should respect their decision. It's a vast Arab world out there, and we must recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to security. We must recognize the right of the Palestinian people to self-determination. In what form? Let the Palestinians, with their friends the Arabs, decide on that. ... Q. There's been a wide perception that differences over the American SDI program have been one of the major obstacles to a START Treaty. Have you made any progress in resolving differences over SDI at this summit? If so, exactly what progress has been made? And do you still continue to believe that that may be a major obstacle in reaching a START Treaty? GORBACHEV: In responding to your last question I say yes, I do, because it means destabilization and it does n't meet normal logic to reduce strategic offensive arms on land and to build a bridge for such arms into outer space. Although the Americans say that this is a purely defensive weapon, we do not think that is. ... Allegedly the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side is ready to share its secrets with us. And I said to the president at that time, I said, `` Permit me, Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, not to agree with you and to call in question that statement of yours. Why? Because right now we ca n't even agree on how to verify sea-based cruise missiles on two types of vessels because you're not ready to agree. So how can we rely on your divulging all of your secrets concerning SDI? That's just not serious, it's beyond the framework of reality.'' ...
