sed: _ <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> spent the month before the April 17 attack on the Faw peninsula moving troops all around the country, generally toward the north When they were ready, the Iraqis used their superior roads and military logistical system to send 50,000 to 60,000 troops streaming back south to <LOCATION> Faw </LOCATION> in one coordinated movement. `` They set up the Iranians masterfully,'' one official said. `` The Iranians never saw it coming.'' `` They achieved surprise,'' a second official added. `` In the course of this plan, they moved units around in ways that Iranian intelligence were likely to be deceived, then reassembled these units in a stealthy and rather sudden way. ... `` And they just ran over the Iranians like a steamroller running over a cockroach. It was really something. They had expected it -LRB- the operation -RRB- to take five days and it took them a day and a half.'' This source noted the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> military had received `` an awfully lot of bad press'' in the past, `` but our conclusion has been that they've gotten steadily better. We have observed with interest the maturation of the Iraqi armed forces as an entity.'' _ In the course of retaking the <LOCATION> Faw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION>, `` the Iraqis digested real quickly the fact the Iranians really did n't fight very well,'' one official said Thus emboldened, the Iraqis set up another assault operation and punched through Iranian lines near <LOCATION> Basra </LOCATION> on May 25, once again routing Iranian forces. `` This was another steamroller,'' an official said. `` It took the Iranians a couple of months to capture -LRB- this area -RRB-, with 60,000 to 65,000 dead. The Iraqi army and air force recaptured it in five hours.'' _ The Iraqis recently provided yet another example of their willingness to become more aggressive, mounting a major air strike against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Larak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> oil terminal Iraqi jet fighters have struck the terminal before. What made the May 14 attack different, the sources said, was the willingness of the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> pilots to slow down, fly low and use heavy iron bombs instead of guided missiles. The bombs pack much more explosive power than missiles like the Exocet and the result was that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> `` just drilled'' several huge oil tankers, putting them out of commission. _ <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> appears to be suffering real recruitment problems in convincing its youth to join the Revolutionary Guard for duty at the front lines The Iranians have been `` equipment-poor'' for some time; `` now they're becoming a people-poor armed force,'' one official said. _ <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is going out of its way to monitor the location of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships and refraining from attacks on merchant vessels if <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships are close enough to intervene, the sources said
