<HEAD>Church of England To Drop Controversial Anonymous Essay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> said Wednesday it will drop the traditional anonymous preface from its next directory because a theologian committed suicide after using the last one to criticize the archbishop of <LOCATION> Canterbury </LOCATION>. A joint statement by the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION>, which oversee church investments and assets, said the commentary was `` no longer a viable option.'' Asked to elaborate, a spokesman cited `` a lot of publicity and the search by the media for the author and the tragic death of <PERSON> Gareth </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity. The preface will be dropped from the 1989-90 edition of <PERSON> Crockford </PERSON>'s Clerical Directory, the official biennial list of Anglican clergy, but no decision has been made on whether to eliminate it permanently, the statement said. `` It has only been dropped for the 1989 edition to allow us more time to consider,'' the spokesman said. `` We shall consider the position again later.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a 68-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> canon, was found dead Dec. 7, five days after the 1987-88 edition of the directory appeared with his preface. It accused Archbishop of Canterbury <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> of being indecisive and overly influenced by liberal pressure groups, and of surrounding himself with liberal bishops. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> is spiritual leader of the church and leads the world's 70 million Anglicans, including 3 million American Episcopalians. The preface attacked moves within the state church toward ordaining women as priests, an issue it said was spreading disunity through the Anglican communion. Although the article was not signed, suspicion fell on <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> because of his stature in the church's conservative wing, his influential position and his academic distinction. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, 66, often has criticized Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s conservative policies, and the preface was widely interpreted as the beginning of a campaign to bring about his retirement and prevent a liberal from succeeding. Bishops and archbishops customarily retire on their 70th birthday. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> denied to colleagues and reporters that he wrote the preface, but was found dead in the garage of his home with a hose leading into his car from the exhaust pipe. Church officials later confirmed he was the author. He did not leave a suicide note, but wrote in a diary four days before his death: `` I should be lucky to weather this business through without disaster.'' A strong clue to authorship was the preface's informed criticism of divisions among Episcopalians in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> following ordination of women priests there. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> had been a visiting professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> since 1975. The Church Commissioners and <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> said they considered publishing a signed commentary in the next directory, but decided against it.
