<HEAD>Reagan Softens Criticism of Human Rights; Surprises Refuseniks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, to the surprise of some refuseniks, said Wednesday that emigration barriers preventing people from leaving the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> may be the result of bureacratic snags rather than deliberate Kremlin policy. In a summit-finale news conference, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said that it was General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> who changed his view of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> as an `` evil empire.'' He said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, his partner at four summit meetings, was `` different than previous Soviet leaders have been.'' The president said he hoped to conclude a U.S.-Soviet treaty to cut strategic nuclear arsenals by half before leaving office, but said it was more important to get a good agreement than to meet a January deadline. Winding up his first visit to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> answered questions at a news conference under hot television lights in a ballroom of the <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the American Embassy residence where he stayed during his five-day visit here. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> refused to rule out the possibility of a fifth summit before leaving office in eight months. `` Something else might come up that necessitates our getting together and settling something other than that particular treaty,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. He was referring to the Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty -LRB- START -RRB-, still being negotiated by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` So, no one can say, no, there will be no need for a summit,'' the president added. Avoiding any direct criticism of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership believed that his meetings in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with Soviet dissidents, refuseniks and others constituted interference in internal matters. The topic had been a centerpiece of his activities here, but abruptly ended after a speech Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. At his news conference, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was asked repeatedly about his comment a day earlier about dissidents and refuseniks, people who have been denied visas and often lose their jobs or are otherwise punished for merely seeking permission to leave or speaking out against the Soviet system. `` I'm not blaming you; I'm blaming bureaucracy,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had told a Soviet questioner. `` We have the same type of thing happen in our country ...'' Asked Wednesday if he thought the problem merely was one of bureaucratic intransigence instead of a deliberate policy, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` No, I ca n't say that _ it's one I do n't know that much about the system.'' The questioner persisted, asking if he were n't `` letting Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> off a little easy on just saying it's a bureaucracy?'' `` I just have to believe that in any government some of us do find ourselves bound in by bureaucracy, and then sometimes you have to stomp your foot and say, unmistakably, I want it done. `` And then maybe you get through with it. But I have great confidence in his ability to do that,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. However, his answer met immediate skepticism. <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON>, a Chicago-born Jew who has been trying to get his family out of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> since 1975, said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s answer was `` naive. Maybe that's a bad word to use, may it's just innocent.'' <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON> said `` I personelly believe that it is Soviet policy. None of it is accidental and none of it is purely bureaucratic.'' <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON>, a Soviet refusenik, asked if she felt the bureacracy was responsible, said, `` Of course not. The bureaucracy has nothing to do with it.'' She speculated that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> merely did not want to spoil some agreement with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on human rights. `` My impression was that he just did n't want to anger our side more,'' she said. `` My feeling is as if some agreement is reached and he does not want to hamper it by saying nasty things.'' <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON>'s family was to have been visited by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> until Soviet authorities passed word that the family would never be allowed to leave if <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> paid a call. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met with reporters shortly after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. At the first news conference he had ever held in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader noted with pleasure that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had retracted his characterization of this country as an `` evil empire.''
