<HEAD>Critics Say State Lacks Coordinated Plan; AIDS Measure on June 7
Ballot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fraziear is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 AIDS activist <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> marched into the governor's office and offered a handful of condoms to the receptionist. `` I'd like to give these to the governor. It's the only thing we've been offered for safety in six years,'' said <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> resident who was among those calling for more action against AIDS. There is growing frustration in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> among the medical community, victims' advocacy groups and AIDS patients over government efforts they say are fractured, adrift in a leadership vacuum and hampered by the governor's conservativism. Against that background, supporters of political extremist <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> have for the second time placed an AIDS initiative on the statewide ballot that would allow medical authorities to quarantine victims of acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Voters will decide the issue, Proposition 69, on June 7. The first such measure was rejected overwhelmingly two years ago. Critics accuse Republican Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> of worrying more about offending conservative voters than saving homosexuals and intravenous drug users who are hit hardest by AIDS. <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> boasts of increasing AIDS spending, up to $ 65 million this fiscal year from $ 3.4 million four years ago and almost 50 percent more than the next four states with high AIDS caseloads combined. He has included $ 75 million in AIDS funds in his 1988-89 budget proposal. A <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> study put <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s AIDS allocation for the 1987-88 fiscal year at $ 58 million, lower than the governor's figure but far higher than <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s appropriation of $ 16.4 million. <LOCATION> Flori