ene. <PERSON> Fraziear </PERSON> said AIDS, by its nature, is fraught with politics. `` We are dealing with subjects that are not generally discussed in mixed company. ... You get a lot of built-in fears that you do n't get with other programs,'' she said She characterized the state as balancing opposing interests and insisted politics have n't interfered with the mission of education, testing and research. But with health care for AIDS victims alone costing an estimated $ 1 billion, and with the epidemic expected to strike 35,000 more Californians by 1991, AIDS experts say the state is n't doing nearly enough. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadden </PERSON>, an assistant to state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberti </PERSON> and a recognized AIDS expert in the Capitol, said the state's low profile forces county health officers and volunteer groups to take the lead. `` To put it bluntly, I wish we could get rid of the state Office of AIDS and put the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> of AIDS in charge,'' <PERSON> Hadden </PERSON> said. `` I think they're much more aggressive.''
