<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Bedouin couple invoked the honor of their desert tribe in demanding the death of an unwanted son-in-law, a prosecutor said today as the two went on trial of charges of soliciting murder. <PERSON> Suad </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ghada </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, are accused of plotting to kill their daughter's husband and his family and asking that photos and body parts be sent back as proof their honor had been restored. No one was hurt. Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dimitrouleas </PERSON> today quoted from secretly taped conversations he said showed the plot was serious. `` ` In <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, he would be bones in the dirt,'' he quoted <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON> as saying of his son-in-law. `` ` If he continues to live, he will destroy my life.''' Police said <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON>, 46, had hired a detective to kill his son-in-law, <PERSON> Mouataz </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdulsalam </PERSON>, his younger sister and his mother, Mrs. <PERSON> Tawaneh </PERSON>'s sister. The detective was secretly cooperating with authorities. The alleged plot was broken up and the Tarawnehs, who left <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> 18 years ago, were arrested in February on charges of conspiracy and solicitation to commit murder. The Tarawnehs' daughter, <PERSON> Raniah </PERSON>, had backed out of an arranged marriage and run off with her Syrian cousin <PERSON> Abdulsalam </PERSON> in 1986 at age 17. The two settled in <LOCATION> Tamarac </LOCATION>. Tradition required the insult be avenged, authorities said. Defense attorney <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Spadaro </PERSON> portrayed <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON> as a heavy drinker and who did not necessarily mean what he said. `` This case involves severe family problems,'' said <PERSON> Spadaro </PERSON>.
