<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     06-01 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Extremists Burn Buildings, Kill Policeman To Disrupt
Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sinhalese extremists on Wednesday burned more than 15 government buildings, stabbed a policeman to death and injured eight people with a bomb in attacks aimed at stopping provincial elections. The government responded by ordering police and security forces to shoot on sight anyone caught destroying government property. The elections are scheduled for Thursday to comply with a provision of a peace accord aimed at ending the minority Tamils' five-year insurgency Extremists among the majority Sinhalese say the pact made too many concessions to the Tamils and have vowed to kill anyone who supports it. Government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said explosions and fire also damaged three trains bound for <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> on Wednesday. One of the trains was stopped by three gun-wielding youths in <LOCATION> Nebomob </LOCATION>, 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, said the officials and travelers. The youths, believed to be Sinhalese extremists, ordered passengers off the train and then set two of the coaches ablaze with gasoline. No injuries were reported. The policeman was stabbed by three Sinhalese in the southern town of <LOCATION> Galle </LOCATION>, said a police spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said one Sinhalese extremist was shot to death in an encounter with police north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> and a second died when a firebomb he was going to throw at a government building just south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> blew up in his hand. In another attack, four government officials and four policemen were seriously injured when a bomb went off in <LOCATION> Nuwara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eilya </LOCATION>'s town hall 60 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> as poll workers prepared for Thursday's voting. Police blamed the attack on the nationalist <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The front told people in the election area to stay inside for 36 hours and put up posters threatening to kill anyone who tried to vote. The police spokesman said more than 15 government buildings were set ablaze by the Sinhalese extremists, mostly in western and southern districts. The buildings included post offices, development offices and town halls, he said. Businessmen said extremists ordered them to shutter their shops, and many merchants said they complied for fear of reprisal. Some of the shops opened later in the day. Government announcements on state-run radio and television said police `` have been given orders to shoot on sight any person engaged in the destruction of public property'' and said the elections would go ahead. The voting Thursday is to elect new district councils in the western and central provinces. The capital at <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> in the western province. More than 3.6 million voters are eligible to vote in the elections to choose 158 representatives. The balloting was called for in the peace accord signed on July 29, 1987 by Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and Sri Lankan President <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>. The signing led to rioting in which several hundred people were killed or injured. The government blamed the Sinhalese front for instigating the riots. The violence on Wednesday was the worst since those riots. The front has been blamed for the deaths of more than 300 people since the pact was signed, many of them government officials or members of <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Several candidates were killed before district council elections April 28 in four other regions. Tamil rebels have been waging a guerrilla war since 1983 for more political autonomy or an independent homeland in northern and eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million population, say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who control the government and military. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has become involved because it is the dominant regional power and because its 60 million ethnic Tamils are sympathetic to the Sri Lankan cause. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has sent more than 50,000 troops to the island to enforce the accord, but they are posted in the north and east to deal with Tamil problems. The Sinhalese front was outlawed after an abortive attempt in 1971 to overthrow the Sri Lankan government. It has been regrouping in recent years and has been blamed for a series of violent acts, including the attempted assassination of <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON> in August 1987.
