ich bore within them a terrible threat to the very existence of mankind and to peace, became more positive and acquired positive dynamism. The two most powerful nations began to reform their relationship in their own interest and in the interest of the world community at large. ... The major result is a continuation of dialogue, which now encompasses all of the key issues of world politics, of bilateral relations. This meeting, once again, demonstrated the fact that we are indulging in a realistic dialogue. ... Also characteristic, and this you will find in the final document ... the concept that in this dialogue of ours ... we are laying down prerequisites, the bricks, so to say, for the building of our future relationship. It is a sign of movement into the 21st century. Now, what have we achieved specifically? I would mention the fact that we have completed the process concerning medium - and shorter-range missiles, and this fourth meeting gave an added impetus to the process and we exchanged instruments of ratification This is not simply a formality, and let me just use a solemn formula ... that completion of the procedures and introduction into force of the INF -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate-Range </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- treaty has turned the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> meeting into a watershed political event in the Soviet-American dialogue and in world politics as a whole. It is not only the peoples of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that can congratulate themselves, but also their allies and the entire world public, the entire world community. It is a common victory for reason and realism. And it has become possible because today, on all continents, in every nation, in every country, regardless of social choice and of other values, which each people chooses for itself, there is a common understanding and awareness that the world had reached the brink and that it had to be stopped, that event had to be stopped and the door had to be opened leading in another direction towards a nuclear free and non-violent world and towards making international relations more healthy. Many made their real and substantial contribution to achieving this major victory. And I must note these facts and also mention the contribution of the press, even when the press posed the most difficult questions before the negotiations, that, too, was a necessary contribution that helped to make the dialogue more concrete, more convincing in finding solutions, finding new arguments in elaborating the forms of verification and control. ... The president and I ... have approved a joint statement. It summarizes what _ the advances made since <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and what has been achieved here in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. At the same time, this statement confirms a sort of agenda for the Soviet-American dialogue for the future. It is, in short, an important political document which hallmarks a whole phase in our relations. The most important points in it are those clauses which relate to the importance of building up political dialogue between the nations, intensifying the talks and negotiations and then I would mention further _ I would note progress made in the sphere of disarmament. This is a very difficult process, especially if you take the question of strategic offensive arms. It's not an easy dialogue. ... I must state very firmly that step-by-step we are moving toward a treaty on strategic offensive arms. ... I will say that if we effectively conduct our business, and if the present administration _ and of course, this applies to both countries _ if we act effectively, using all of our possibilities and opportunities, we can achieve a treaty. ...
