<HEAD>Abandoned World War I Gun Battery is Stage for Medieval Drama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SULLIVAN'S ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Battery Thomson, nestled on the shores of <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s Island flanking <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> harbor, was built years ago for a German attack that never came. But on recent evenings, the World War I-era cement and stone bunker has become the torch-lighted stage for portraying a much older conflict: `` Wat Tyler,'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sewell </PERSON>'s dramatic account of a peasant revolt in 14th century <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Running Horse Productions of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> is staging the premiere of the play as part of <LOCATION> Piccolo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION>, a companion festival to <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>'s Spoleto Festival U.S.A. The production deals with the 1381 uprising in which <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> marched with an army of 10,000 serfs to confront King <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, then 14. <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiedergott </PERSON>, who recently did a pilot for a new CBS-TV series called `` Limited Partners,'' plays the role of <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Winley </PERSON> is <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, an itinerant priest who inspired <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Horvitz </PERSON>, who recently appeared in the movie `` Summer School,'' plays the king. Of the 20 cast members, 12 are from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and eight from <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. The actors are volunteering their time for the production. `` We're doing a $ 50,000 show for $ 18,000,'' said <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> LeGrande </PERSON>, one of the co-producers. `` It would cost $ 75,000 in <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION>'' Cast members helped build risers for seating, helped assemble scaffolding for light towers and spent hours in the hot sun clearing a battery of weeds and broken glass. The audience is escorted through a cave-like door of the bunker and through a hallway lined with candles. On the other side with underbrush lining the battery, the scene takes on the aura of a medieval castle. Before being taken over by the production, the battery was a hangout for youths who live on the island where master of the macabre <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Poe </PERSON> wrote `` <PERSON> Annabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'' and `` The Gold Bug.'' Locals on the island of weathered beach houses have opened their doors to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> cast. `` We've been getting a lot of attention because it's an unusual project as a whole,'' <PERSON> LeGrande </PERSON> said. Local merchants have donated food, neighbors have put up relatives of cast members while 13 actors are living in a beach house provided by a resident. For <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> MacHugh </PERSON>, who has appeared in a number of TV series and has the part of <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Straw </PERSON> in the play, the production is a chance to perform away from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` It's a new piece without the <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> environment,'' he said. `` We get to work with something untouched, and we get <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s Island too.''
