<HEAD>Money Stores to Accept Fine Payments on Traffic Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Traffic scofflaws are getting relief _ not from the fines but from lines at court. Three <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Money </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> soon will accept fine payments in a program that will help clear 36th <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which processed more than 400,000 traffic violations last year, Chief Judge <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakoor </PERSON> said. The Money Stores, owned by <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION>'s only minority-owned bank, will get a 50-cent fee from each ticket. Traffic violations can be paid by mail, but people too poor to maintain bank accounts are unable do so because fines must be paid with a check or money order. Thirty percent are paid in person, <PERSON> Shakoor </PERSON> said. `` The 36th District Court is a people's court, and we intend to provide more community-oriented services that will ultimately make the court run more smoothly,'' <PERSON> Shakoor </PERSON> said. Beginning June 13, motorists can pay fines on all traffic violations. The program may be expanded for parking violations. First Independence, which opened the <ORGANIZATION> Money </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> more than a year ago to provide banking services to lower-income <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> residents, lost $ 500,000 on the stores last year and expects to lose $ 230,000 this year. The fees collected from the fine payments will help, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, chairman of First Independence. The Money Stores were chosen for the program because the facilities have computer systems that are compatible with the court's, <PERSON> Shakoor </PERSON> said, adding officials eventually hope to make the service available at other banking institutions. <PERSON> Shakoor </PERSON> said he knew of no other program like <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s in the country.
