<HEAD>Airport Parking Cashiers Stole Up to $2 Million, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parking cashiers at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> skimmed as much as $ 2 million from customers' parking fees by substituting low-value tickets for higher-priced ones, court documents said. The cashiers obtained bogus parking tickets by rolling shopping carts over sensors and then traded $ 2 stubs for those turned in by customers who paid up to $ 100, according to documents unsealed Tuesday. The cashiers pocketed up to $ 250 an hour, police said in affidavits seeking search warrants. More than 30 employees of <ORGANIZATION> Parking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Concepts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the 25,000-space airport parking concession, were indicted May 19 on charges of embezzling city funds. Officials estimated that as much as $ 2 million had been skimmed. According to the documents, new applicants for parking cashier positions were forced to pay up to $ 3,000 to gain the $ 7-an-hour jobs, but were assured by managers that they could make that money back through the alleged embezzlement scheme. Twenty-three defendants pleaded innocent to embezzlement charges Tuesday; preliminary hearings were scheduled for June and July. Three others were arraigned last week; two were to enter pleas June 7. Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> declined comment on the status of the remaining defendants. Police infiltrated Parking Concepts last June after an anonymous tip alerted authorities to the scheme, Detective <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
