<FIRST>r a AM-Transplants-Growth     06-01 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transplants-Growth,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Trying To Help Kidney Kids Grow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Transplants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They're alive and well, but children who undergo kidney transplants are also extremely short because the medication they take to ensure the transplant is n't rejected hinders their growth, doctors say. Since young kidney recipients want to grow normally, doctors are trying new therapies, with some success, to help them in body and spirit. `` They're taller and they're much happier,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Amir </PERSON> <PERSON> Tejani </PERSON>, director of renal services at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. About one-fourth of all young kidney recipients can be treated successfully without a steroid commonly combined with the potent anti-rejection drug cyclosporine, <PERSON> Tejani </PERSON> reported Tuesday at the annual conference of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physicians </ORGANIZATION>. The steroid, known as prednisone, inhibits the growth plate in the bone from functioning normally. It also causes acne and puffiness, most noticeably in the face. `` This is a very important study since the whole point of doing transplants is to achieve growth,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, a nephrologist at <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` Even for a third of them to grow normally, then by all means we should be doing this for our kids or at least trying,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunsicker </PERSON>, the society's president. Like children suffering from other serious illnesses, children with kidney failure tend to be extraordinarily short, sometimes barely topping 4 feet. By the time they undergo a transplant, it's often too late for these children to catch up on past growth. Even if they receive transplants at a very young age, the medication necessary for helping to prevent their bodies' immune systems from attacking the new organ stunts their growth. Perhaps the best-known case involves <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, star of the former television series `` Diff ` rent Strokes The 19-year-old actor, who's undergone two kidney transplants, is under 5 feet tall. `` The issue is a big one'' for these children, said Dr. <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Greifer </PERSON>, medical director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kidney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. `` A lot of the patients, especially the younger ones, want to take the risk -LRB- of rejection -RRB- for the extra inches.'' Some patients, in fact, cheat on their medication in a desperate attempt to improve their appearance, according to <PERSON> Tejani </PERSON>. `` You ca n't tell them it does n't matter -LRB- if they're short -RRB- when it matters to them,'' <PERSON> Greifer </PERSON> said. `` You ca n't tell them the world is made up of small people when Americans are getting taller.'' About 1,200 youngsters 16 and under experience kidney failure every year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Greifer </PERSON>. Six hundred to 800 of them eventually receive new kidneys; they comprise fewer than 9 percent of the total number of kidney transplants performed annually. The operation is quite successful. One year after transplantation, up to 85 percent of them still have properly functioning kidneys, according to experts. For his research, <PERSON> Tejani </PERSON> studied 53 children and selected 30 whose transplanted kidneys were functioning well enough to undergo the experiment. The 30 were taken off prednisone. Twenty-three of them proved to be treatable solely with cyclosporine at the time. However, nine of the 23 had to return to prednisone later, after experiencing mild episodes of organ rejection, <PERSON> Tejani </PERSON> said. The remaining 14 _ a little more than one-fourth of the original 53 children in the study _ have been off prednisone for up to 4 -LCB- years without any episodes of organ rejection or side effects, according to <PERSON> Tejani </PERSON>. More important, all of them have grown, including one 17-year-old boy who has reached 5 feet, 8 inches. In patients unable to be weaned off prednisone, <PERSON> Tejani </PERSON> has administered growth hormone, enabling them to catch up on some of their lost growth. Doctors at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> also have begun giving growth hormone to certain kidney transplant patients as well as children on dialysis. `` The data seems good,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, a clinical fellow at <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION>. `` There seems to be hope.''
</TEXT>
