s imprisonment in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Guillo </PERSON> also had been convicted of espionage after entering <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> with the guerrillas. Guillo, 45, was convicted Jan. 4 and sentenced to 10 years imprisonment. <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON> was sentenced to seven years. <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Grazia </PERSON>, reached in <LOCATION> Trieste </LOCATION>, said she planned to fly to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> to await her son's return as soon as she receives confirmation that he has been freed. `` I'm still shaken up, I can hardly believe the news,'' she said.
