<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s right-wing rebels claimed Wednesday their guerrilla forces attacked an major Mozambican army base, tore up railway tracks and killed 28 people, including a British military instructor. In a statement released in <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION>, the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Mozambican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> said 16 army regulars, nine <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> support troops, two <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> advisers and the Briton were killed Sunday at the base at <LOCATION> Magude </LOCATION>, 75 miles north of the capital of <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it had no information to corroborate the claim that a British military instructor was killed. The rebel note identified the Cubans as <PERSON> Alexandre </PERSON> <PERSON> Gimenez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frederico </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>. The Briton's name was given as <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thone </PERSON>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, told the national news agency AIM that his embassy had no record of anyone named <PERSON> Thone </PERSON> and had received no first-hand report of any Briton being killed or injured. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> said a British team trains Mozambican soldiers at a base in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> but does not have military personnel stationed in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, except for an attache at the embassy. In the rebel statement, the group denied charges by the <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s Marxist government that the rebels still receive South African backing despite a 1984 non-aggression pact between <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. It has claimed earlier killings of British military instructors posted in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> have sent support troops to aid the Mozambican army in its 11-year campaign to stop the bloody <PERSON> bush </PERSON> insurgency.
