<NOTE>EDS: Inserts new grafs 5-6 with Rowny quotes</NOTE>
<HEAD>Summit Produced Some Marginal Advances on Arms Control Front</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th graf bgng: In a ... to UPDATE with
Rowny quotes. Picks up 6th graf pvs bgng: Besides modest ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> reported progress Wednesday over two obstacles to a strategic arms deal, but ended their fourth summit divided over the main impediment, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Star Wars program. `` I would hope that before the year is out that we could eliminate the differences that still exist,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. But there seemed little prospect for any imminent breakthrough. After four days of intense talks, the two leaders ordered their negotiators to return to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on July 12 to work on a proposed treaty to cut superpower nclear arsenals by 30 percent to 50 percent. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told reporters `` it is still possible to sign an agreement in this administration.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` Conversations are still going on and they are still being discussed and I say progress is still being made or we would n't be talking as we are.'' In a 24-page joint statement, the two leaders announced `` achievement of substantial additional common ground'' on two of the five major disputed areas on the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty -LRB- START -RRB-, ways of monitoring mobile missiles and counting nuclear-tipped cruise missiles on warplanes. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms negotiator <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowny </PERSON> said there was `` a lot of room'' to go in the two areas. And he said `` we didn ` t get anywhere'' on the two biggest obstacles to a treaty: keeping track of submarine-fired cruise missiles and Soviet objections to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Star Wars missile-defense program, formally known as the Strategic Defense Inititiative. Besides modest progress on START, the two leaders inched ahead on other arms control issues. They exchanged ratification protocols for the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty -LRB- INF -RRB- to eliminate medium-range nuclear missiles, which was signed at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit last December and ratified by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last Friday and by the Soviet assembly of presidents 17 hours later. During the summit, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also signed two lesser arms control agreements, one requiring advance notifice of ballistic missile tests and another to tighten verification procedures for a 1974 treaty limiting nuclear tests to 150 kilotons. On the START treaties, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said they had restated opposition to deployment of Soviet SS-24 and SS-25 missiles. `` It is the position of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that such missiles should be banned unless the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> can reach agreement on provisions which provide for effective verification and strict numerical limits on the number of nuclear weapons carried by such missiles,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, in a briefing paper given to reporters, said that acceptable verification rules would require, among other things, restricting mobile missiles to specific geographical areas, means to assure that spy satellites can keep tabs on all such weapons, and the right to inspect sites to investigate suspected violations. The two sides remained far apart on Star Wars and how to negotiate reductions in conventional armies. `` We have missed a chance to take an important step forward,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told reporters. The <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader, who has used all four meetings with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as forums to air his opposition to <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION>, said he had proposed resolving the problem by exchanging data allowing mutual inspection of facilities where technology for an anti-missile defense is tested. But no strategic arms treaty is possible, he said, without an agreement assuring that development and deployment of strategic defenses does not violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. And a fifth summit would not be possible without a START deal, he said. On the opening day of the talks, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet officials said, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> suggested to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that they exchange data on conventional arms as a means of making drastic cuts, as proposed by the Russians in 1986. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say they will not directly negotiate conventional cuts with the Soviets, because the matter must be agreed upon by the 33 nations taking part in the Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Those talks also include discussion of alleged Soviet violations of human rights provisions of the original conference accord, signed in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> in 1975.
