<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> moved Wednesday to strip <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship from a <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> man accused of being part of an execution squad that murdered unarmed Jews and other civilians for the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> during World War II. <PERSON> Valdis </PERSON> <PERSON> Didrichsons </PERSON> concealed his service in the <ORGANIZATION> Latvian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auxiliary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> in 1941 and 1942 when he entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1950 under the Displaced Persons Act, the government alleged in a complaint filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. A native of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Didrichsons </PERSON> became a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen in August 1956. Assisting in persecution makes a person ineligible to immigrate to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and requires revocation of citizenship. The denaturalization case against <PERSON> Didrichsons </PERSON> is the first step in a process which could lead to deportation. The objective of the <ORGANIZATION> Arajs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kommando </ORGANIZATION>, as the auxiliary unit was known, was to assist in the persecution and murder of people considered to be racially undesirable or enemies of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in occupied <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Nazi-hunting unit, the Office of Special Investigations. <PERSON> Didrichsons </PERSON> assisted in persecution, said the complaint, and concealed his membership in the Kommando when he applied for citizenship as well as when he entered the country. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also has instituted legal proceedings against <PERSON> Konrads </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalejs </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mikelis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirsteins </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, who allegedly served with <PERSON> Didrichsons </PERSON> in the Kommando in 1941.
