<SECOND>AM-UN-Disarmament,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Speakers Call On Soviets And U.S. To Ban Nuclear Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates to a special <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> session on disarmament on Wednesday urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to ban underground weapons tests and scrap their nuclear arsenals. Speakers began addressing the special session as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> concluded their <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit meeting with an impasse on achieving major cuts in strategic nuclear weapons. But the assembly praised the superpower treaty eliminating intermediate-range nuclear weapons as a breakthrough because it scraps a whole class of nuclear weapons for the first time. Prime Minister <PERSON> Ingvar </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> called for complete nuclear disarmament and said the use of nuclear arms could threaten the survival of civilization. `` One can not reach peace by frightening other countries,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> could and should have a central role in the sphere of disarmament, and is the most appropriate organization to carry out verification functions on behalf of the international community,'' he said. It can provide unique services, as a repository of data and source of impartial observers and experts, he said. He called for 50 percent cuts in strategic weapons, complete abolition of all tactical nuclear weapons, prevention of a nuclear arms race in outer space, a comprehensive nuclear test ban, the signing the nuclear nonproliferation treaty, and the removal of nuclear weapons from naval vessels. <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON> also condemned the use of chemical weapons in the Iran-Iraq war and said the buildup of anti-personnel lasers also must be stopped. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the only nation that has been the target of an atomic attack, said his people pray for disarmament. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s constitution prohibits the presence or development of nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> announced that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> plans to convene an international conference with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to share Japanese technology in seismology to verify nuclear testing. He said it could serve as step toward establishing a global system for verification of nuclear testing. He said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would increase its assistance to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to prevent conflicts, noting that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> recently contributed $ 20 million to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, including $ 5 million for use in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> where the world body mediated a settlement. The Japanese leader said he was considering the dispatch of personnel for election supervision, transportation, communication and medical services to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> delivered the opening address as chairman of the non-aligned movement. He condemned the superpowers for the nuclear arms race and said military spending should be diverted to development. He said the international community must work toward achieving a nuclear-free world with the help of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the multilateral Conference on Disarmament. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> called for a comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty _ a measure opposed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ and he opposed the militarization of outer space _ a reference to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space-based missile defense initiative, or `` Star Wars.'' He called for the establishment of nuclear-free zones, including <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. More than 25 heads of state and government will address the 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in the next two weeks in the third special session on disarmament in 10 years. The world body then will adopt resolutions on disarmament, from nuclear to chemical, and steps to achieve it.
