<HEAD>Congress Urged To Regulate Test-Tube Baby Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Physicians are overpromising success to women desperate to have children and there is need for congressional oversight of the $ 30 million to $ 40 million test-tube baby industry, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was told Wednesday. `` Under the best of circumstances, infertile couples already face invasive medical procedures, the risk of dangerous complications and low success rates,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore. `` Frustrated couples, many at an emotional breaking point, should n't also have to face those who would exploit their faith in modern medicine. <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on regulation and business opportunities, said he wants to determine what role the government should play in protecting would-be parents from unscrupulous clinics. He called attention to a recent study that found more than half of the 169 clinics in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> performing in-vitro fertilization -LRB- IVF -RRB- in 1987 never produced a baby. `` Despite advances in technology and the claims made by some clinics, the chance of having a baby from IVF still hovers at one in ten,'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said. `` This slim opportunity costs most couples thousands of dollars. The subcommittee has heard of couples spending over $ 22,000 without yielding a baby in the bassinet.'' The infertility study for the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> showed Americans spent $ 1 billion last year to combat infertility. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, who directed the <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> study, told the subcommittee the chances of becoming clinically pregnant _ when a fetus's heartbeat is detected by ultrasound machines _ is about 17 percent, and a woman still faces a one in three chance that the pregnancy is ectopic or that it will end in a miscarriage or stillbirth An ectopic pregnancy is one outside the uterus. Therefore, he said, a woman's chance of taking home a test-tube baby is about 6 percent. He said that infertility, generally defined as the inability of a couple to conceive after 12 months of intercourse without contraception, affects an estimated 2.4 million married couples and an unknown number of would-be parents among unmarried couples and singles. <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>'s subcommittee also heard from a woman, <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckhardt </PERSON>, who said a fertility expert over a four-year span told her seven times that she was pregnant, but that each time would find the fetus had been `` absorbed.'' Her husband, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>, said they had spent $ 35,000 on infertility treatments, only to learn from another doctor that Mrs. <PERSON> Eckhardt </PERSON> probably never had been pregnant. The doctor, she said, `` out and out lied to use, telling us I was pregnant. `` Each time I felt like I had failed again, that my own body was killing our baby,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Eckhardt </PERSON> said. `` But then I would get that little urge again and want a baby so badly that I would go through anything. `` It's hard to explain to other people, but when you want a baby so badly and you're afraid you may never be able to have one, it's all you can think about It affects the way you see the whole world.''
