<HEAD>U.S. Posts High Pregnancy, Abortion Rates, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pregnancy and abortion rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are among the highest found in a new study of Western nations, averaging 2.56 pregnancies and 0.76 abortions for each woman of reproductive age. Only <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> showed higher pregnancy rates, with 4.33 and 3.23 respectively, in the study of 17 industrialized countries. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> also had a higher abortion rate, 2.24, as did <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, with 0.80, according to researchers at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guttmacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> organization that studies fertility issues. The study appears in the current issue of the institute's Family Planning Perspectives. The lowest pregnancy rates appeared in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, with 1.64, and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, with 1.68. The lowest abortion rates were in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, with 0.15, and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, with 0.18. Abortion is outlawed by <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and another nation in the study, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, although abortions are still relatively easy to to obtain in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, the researchers wrote. Substantial limitations are imposed by <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, the scientists said. The other countries in the survey were <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. The study was based on the year of most recent abortion data, which was 1983 for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Researchers also compared contraceptive use among the 17 nations plus <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Some method of contraception was used in 1982 by about 54 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women of reproductive age, defined as ages 15 to 44, researchers said. That level ranked relatively low, along with those of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. About 37 percent of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women used a contraceptive pill, an intra-uterine device or male or female sterilization, a `` medium'' level of use in comparison to the other countries. That showing is largely due to widespread use of sterilization, researchers said.
