<HEAD>US Strategist Cautions Against Philippines-Vietnam Tradeoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To get American military forces out of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> should offer much more than shutting down the biggest Soviet overseas base at <LOCATION> Cam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military strategist <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON> said Wednesday. A Cam Ranh-Philippines tradeoff by the superpowers `` would be very much in the Soviet interest but not necessarily ours,'' said <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON>, a retired air force lieutenant general and national security adviser in the Ford administration. `` The Russians do n't need that -LRB- Cam Ranh -RRB- nearly as much as we do the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>,'' he said. Scowcroft spoke at a news conference marking the issuance of a new expert study on forthcoming U.S.-Philippines base negotiations produced for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Foreign Relations, a non-profit, non-partisan organization. The study noted that the massive Soviet military presence at <LOCATION> Cam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> is used as justification for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military presence in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and vice versa. Analysts have said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s July 1986 Asian policy speech suggesting a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pullout from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> implied an offer to reduce the Soviet presence in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. The Philippine bases, <LOCATION> Clark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> air base and <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> naval station, are vital for deploying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces to the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> a