<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has dealt a serious setback to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's anti-cocaine program by refusing to allow use of a `` safe and effective herbicide'' against coca-producing areas in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. `` We think the short-term impact is serious,'' said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON>, alluding to <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON>'s decision last week not to sell to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government the herbicide tebuthurion in a coca eradication campaign focused mainly in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Huallaga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> She said the firm, which is the sole manufacturer of the chemical, should reconsider its decision in light of the serious cocaine problem in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> English </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., expressed outrage over <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION>'s decision The Indianapolis-based company gave no reason for its decision in making the announcement last week, citing only `` a number of practical and policy considerations.'' But Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> told reporters <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> apparently was worried about possible retaliatory measures by `` traffickers or terrorists.'' The company also had come under pressure from environmentalists who were concerned about the ecological impact of the herbicide. Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would have preferred to have worked with the company on resolving its security concerns. She said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> governments have been conducting field tests to identify a safe, effective herbicide for use against coca for several years. Tebuthurion, known informally as `` <PERSON> Spike </PERSON>,'' was considered to be among the safest and most effective, but no final decision had been made about which herbicide should be used, Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` According to our information the safety and effectiveness of spike has been clearly demonstrated and defended by the company. Numerous environmental tests have been carried out in compliance with federal regulations,'' she said. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wrobleski </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for international narcotics matters, said <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> made the decision even though the herbicide has been manufactured for more than 15 years, has been proven safe by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> standards and is widely available in this country for projects such as clearing brush for rights of way. The chemical is sold to other government agencies including the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, she said. Testifying before a House Government Operations subcommittee assessing the war on drugs, Ms. <PERSON> Wrobleski </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers are researching whether to propose legislation that would compel <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> to sell the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <OR