<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Surgeons Wednesday gave up trying to reattach a 5-year-old boy's right arm, torn off at the shoulder, concluding after nine hours in the operating room that the damage to the limb and shoulder was too great. <PERSON> Fidencio </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaurequi </PERSON>, whose arm became caught in a farm machine used to sort cherry tomatoes, was in critical condition at <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. He was expected to remain in the pediatric intensive care unit several days. Three surgeons from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> spent from 3:15 p.m. Tuesday until 12:20 a.m. in the operating room. `` Preliminary procedures had been performed,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKell </PERSON>, vice president of medical affairs. `` Regrettably, the injury was so severe, with so much destruction of the tissue, that it was not possible to rejoin the extremity.'' The child, the son of <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Eustolia </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaurequi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, had gone to a barn at Singletary Farms where his mother was working, according to a co-owner of the 75-acre vegetable farm. `` He stuck his arm into the machine'' and it got caught under the conveyor belt on the roller, said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Singletary </PERSON>, who was outside the barn when the accident occurred Tuesday. The severed limb was retrieved from the sorting machine. `` I had them put ice on his arm ... and I held a shirt up on his arm _ that much I knew to do,'' <PERSON> Singletary </PERSON> said. Rescue workers arrived 13 minutes after the accident was reported and pack