<HEAD>Aviation Industry Holds Conference In Wake Of Aloha Airlines
Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An aviation industry stunned by the in-flight breakup last month of an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet began a formal re-examination Wednesday of how to ensure that aging aircraft are kept safe. More than 350 representatives from airlines, aircraft manufacturers, government agencies and various aviation safety groups launched a three-day conference by debating whether the industry's approach to maintaining the safety of older planes is adequate. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> suggested that a central question which must be resolved is whether to continue the current philosophy that relies heavily on inspections or shift the focus to a system of mandatory repairs or, at some point, mandatory aircraft retirement. Concerns about aging aircraft among the commercial airliner fleets surfaced last month when a 20-foot section of an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 tore away at 24,000 feet. A flight attendant was swept to her death, but the pilots managed to get the plane on the ground. The 19-year-old Aloha plane was one of the oldest <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s in service and had accumulated nearly 90,000 takeoffs and landings. Investigators believe cracking and corrosion in the upper forwared part of the cabin likely caused the section of the plane to peel away during flight. The central question confronting Wednesday's conference centered on why the apparent cracking and corrosion on the Aloha plane were not detected by inspectors. An <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> directive last year had required closer inspection of older aircraft for cabin skin cracking and corrosion. During the three-day meeting, the industry representatives are expected to debate whether aircraft design improvements need to be made and what steps need to be taken to improve the