<HEAD>Hot Line Expands As Calls Accelerate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An AIDS hot line has expanded from 130 operators to 220 to accommodate a rush of calls generated in part by an educational pamphlet mailed to 10 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> homes, officials said. `` We're still in the beginning of the rush,'' said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphries </PERSON>, coordinator for the National AIDS Hotline in Research Triangle Park. `` Not everybody in the country has gotten the pamphlet yet.'' The government pamphlet `` Understanding AIDS'' forced hot line officials to recruit operators through advertisements, flyers and the news media. The 24-hour hot line, 1-800-342-AIDS, offers referrals in English and Spanish for people seeking help in their areas for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Officials expect 2 million calls in 1988. `` I think we're going to be at full capacity once we get everyone trained,'' Ms. <PERSON> Humphries </PERSON> said. `` Things have been going rather smoothly.'' The hot line is run by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> under contract with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. AIDS attacks the body's immune system, leaving it defenseless to many diseases. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. There is no known cure.
