<HEAD>Lack of Equipment, Budget Hurting Drug Interdiction, Congress Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been unable to stem the flood of drugs into this country because of budget cuts and delays in making crucial detection equipment operational, two federal agencies said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Commandant <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> enforcement chief, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee they increasingly were frustrated by their inability to throw more resources into the anti-drug effort. They gave the panel a long list of problems they encountered: patrol boats and planes sitting idle due to a money shortage; surveillance airplanes with cracks in their wings; construction delays at new intelligence centers; and delayed installation of radar balloons along the nation's border with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yost </PERSON>, whose new, fast patrol boats and airplanes are operating at only 55 percent of last year's levels, said it was ironic that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is ready to spend huges sums for an escalation of the military's role in the drug war, but ca n't find $ 60 million to get his vessels in the water and planes in the air full time. `` Turn me loose and do n't give my mission away,'' he told the Government Operations subcommittee on information, justice and agriculture. Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., chairman of the panel, was sharply critical of the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, blaming the agency for delays in installing five radar balloons along the porous <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> border to detect airborne drug smugglers Only one of the five balloons, called aerostats, is in operation. `` This is a terrible failure,'' he told <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON>. `` You are costing us dearly. There's no sense of urgency about this. That's the problem. <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> described a series of delays in site selection, environmental problems, competitive bidding and even roadblocks from other government agencies. `` We had to work around interference with the military and other agencies,'' <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> said. In Alpine, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, he said, there was a problem of interference with a private observatory. In another instance, <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a government agency, initially declined to allow an aerostat on a site. That agency has changed its mind, <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> said. `` Two years later,'' English interjected. When <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> said he spent four months seeking competitive bids for the radar balloons in an effort to save money, English said, `` In effect, you cost us a heck of a lot of money'' because <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> AWACS surveillance planes have had to patrol the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> border to pick up the slack. English said that an AWACS costs $ 7,500 an hour to operate. `` Without a detection system, interceptors and bust -LRB- arrest -RRB- teams are nearly worthless,'' English said. `` You hired pilots, purchased aircraft and hired bust teams who have to sit on the ground for up to two years before they will be able to do their mission. `` It calls into question whether the air interdictioin war is capable of being more than a skirmish in the next two years.'' <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> replied, `` We're trying our darndest to get these things in there. I share your frustration.'' <PERSON> Yost </PERS