<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty-six competitors were eliminated in the first day of the National Spelling Bee today, a contest in which, for once, it was n't just the children who made the mistakes. The 61st annual renewal of the competition began with a record field of 200 contestants. During the third round _ the last of the day _ 43 of them misspelled their way into elimination. Among those making errors were 13-year-old <PERSON> Awilda </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cintron </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ceiba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, who did not begin learning to speak English until the third grade. The eighth-grader misspelled the word strisciando, a musical direction to play in a slurred, smooth manner. As the competition's second round began, bee officials began handing to reporters a list of the words that had been asked during the first round. But the distribution ceased when a reporter pointed out to a tournament official that the list misspelled the word `` hitchhike.'' On the list, the word was spelled `` hitchike.'' `` It was a typing error,'' said bee spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. The first entrant to drop out of the tournament was <PERSON> Monekia </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gause </PERSON>, 11, of <LOCATION> Shallotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, who misspelled the word `` jargon.'' The sixth-grader spelled it `` j-a-r-g-i-n.'' Told she had misspelled the word, she tugged at the sleeves of her pink dress and left the stage `` I never heard it before,'' <PERSON> Monekia </PERSON> said afterward. The first round's only other dropout was <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>, 11, of Mentor, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, who responded `` hitchhick'' when asked to spell `` hitchhike.'' The bee has attracted its usual field of gifted children with enough academic achievements to humble most adults, including its youngest competitor ever. She is <PERSON> Iris </PERSON> <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>, a third-grader from <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, who does n't turn nine until June 20 <PERSON> Iris </PERSON>, whose parents immigrated to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1979 and now own a bookstore, enjoys reading books in English and Chinese when she is n't pursuing one of her other loves: jumping rope. `` Not really,'' she said Tuesday evening when asked if she was nervous. But as if to show that she's only human, she expressed uncertainty about her chances of winning the bee, saying, `` They have some funny words in there.'' This year's field consists of 102 girls and 98 boys from 47 states, the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. It includes <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, 14, of <LOCATION> Oroville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, who received no formal institutional schooling until the third grade, according to the bee's biographical booklet. Although contest rules allow children who are not yet 16 and have not progressed beyond the eighth grade, no one competing in the two-day event is 15 years old yet. Last year's winner was <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Petit </PERSON>, an eighth-grader from <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, who correctly spelled `` staphylococci,'' a type of bacteria. It took 876 words to eliminate the 184 other entrants in the 1987 bee. The 13-year-old <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON>, like all previous winners, was not allowed to re-enter the competition. But there are 20 contestants making their second appearances, and two who are comp