<SECOND>AM-Summit-Rights-Arms,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan's Muted Rights Comments May Be Aimed At Cut In Europe
Forces</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 By muting his criticism of Soviet human rights abuses, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> may be trying to speed up negotiations that would substantially cut <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> forces in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who built a political career bashing <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION> and in his first term called the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> an `` evil empire,'' confounded observers on Tuesday and Wednesday by attributing Kremlin human rights abuses to bureaucratic inertia and praising <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for trying to reform it. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his aides attributed the softening of the president's rhetoric to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efforts to reform the system But the answer to the riddle may lie in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s often-stated preference for `` quiet diplomacy'' and the link that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have established between human rights and the professed desired of both sides to reduce conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, at the opening of the summit on Sunday night, repeated to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> his 1986 proposal for cuts of 500,000 soldiers in the opposing armies of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> and the Kremlin-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>. Nice idea, said the Americans, but such reductions must come through negotiations involving all the allies on both sides, and the ideal forum is the Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> now under way in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. Those talks grew out of the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Accords, in which the Soviets pledged to observe human rights. For 13 years the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has accused the Kremlin of violating the accords, and Soviet officials are now conceding as much, releasing political prisoners and allowing greater public discussion of formerly taboo subjects. Many Americans, including Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>., D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, believe that sharp reductions in conventional forces should accompany the 30 percent to 50 percent cuts in long-range nuclear missiles envisioned in the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction From the American point of view, the main objectives of reducing conventional arms would be a reduction in the 2-to-1 advantage the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact holds on tanks and a reduction in the 380,000 Red Army troops in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Although the edge may have dulled on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s anti-Communist rhetoric, his schedule was designed to emphasize <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concern with human rights: he met with nearly 100 Soviet dissidents at the residence of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> ambassador, he pointedly praised the virtues of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> democracy at every turn, he chatted with with writers, artists and students. And <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials let it be known that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had canceled a meeting with the <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON> family of Jewish refuseniks because a high-ranking <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> official had warned that a visit to their home would kill their application to emigrate. Much of the hardball was being played behind the scenes, said a senior administration official, noting that the American and the Soviet regularly but quietly were engaged in discussion of human rights issues. The president's statements would be hard to explain, unless there was something going on behind the scenes. And his spoken words were particularly puzzling in light of his extra-curricular activities at the summit, which appeared designed to focus attention on Soviet human rights policy, especially the difficulties that Jews face in emigrating. But on Tuesday, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told students at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> that recalcitrant bureaucrats were to blame for Soviet human rights abuses. And under pointed questioning at a news conference on Wednesday, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said similar problems could be found everywhere. `` I just have to believe that in any sort of government some of us do find ourselves bound in by bureaucracy,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. And after four days of talks with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, he expressed confidence that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader was trying and would succeed in improving the situation. Soviet human rights activists attributed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s comments on human rights to naivete. `` The bureaucracy has nothing to do with it,'' said <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON>, whose family had waited in vain for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s visit on Sunday. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his aides may have been calculating that, having made their views known in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, they should tone down the rhetoric in hopes of winning long-sought cuts in Soviet conventional forces in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
