<HEAD>Broadcasters, First Amendment Groups Challenge Rules on Indecency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coalition of broadcasters and other First Amendment advocates told a federal appeals court panel Wednesday that the government's rules on indecent broadcasts are unconstitutionally vague. Attorney <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyk </PERSON> said the groups do not challenge the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s authority to govern indecency on the air, but he said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s policy does not give broadcasters a clear idea what they can air without fear of sanctions. `` What we would like is some guidance'' on what can be broadcast, he told a panel of three <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> judges. `` Broadcasters do not want to risk their licenses.'' The result of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s policy has been to chill fully protected speech, <PERSON> Dyk </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> in April 1987 cracked down on indecent broadcasts with a new policy that went beyond simply prohibiting the `` seven dirty words'' that comedian <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlin </PERSON> once used in a radio broadcast. His monologue led to a 1978 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision on indecency. The agency said it would enforce the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s definition of indecency: `` language or material that depicts or describes, in terms patently offensive as measured by contemporary community standards for the broadcast medium, sexual or excretory activities or organs.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said broadcasts that fit that definition, and not just programs that used the `` seven dirty words,'' could be subject to sanctions unless the programs were broadcast after midnight, when children were not likely to be in the audience. The policy serves `` the government's compelling and well established interest in protecting children's exposure to salacious material,'' said <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Killory </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> general counsel. <PERSON> Killory </PERSON> said the decision to set aside the early morning hours after midnight as `` safe harbor'' represents `` a balancing of a number of interests'' and `` does n't lend itself to a precise mathematical formula.'' Judge <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsburg </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s evidence on the number of children in the late-night radio audience appeared to be `` flimsy,'' but <PERSON> Killory </PERSON> countered that `` even with all the resources in the world ... it would still come down to a judgment call.'' <PERSON> Killory </PERSON> said the commission's policy was aimed at helping protect minors from indecent material but was not designed to displace parents as the primary protectors of children. `` It would be unrealistic to assume parents can supervise their children at all hours of the day and night,'' <PERSON> Killory </PERSON> said. Among the groups joining the petition challenging the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s policy are <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ