<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Glance     06-01 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Glance,0446</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Includes AM-AIDS-Monkeys, a0793; AM-AIDS-Antibodies, a0847;
AM-AIDS-Hotline, a0813; AM-AIDS-Science Academy, a0825.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the latest developments on the AIDS front:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-MONKEYS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The AIDS virus probably did not jump from monkeys to humans but could have infected the common ancestors of humans and monkeys millions of years ago, researchers say. Japanese biologists who have determined the entire genetic code of the AIDS virus that infects African green monkeys found that the monkey AIDS virus differed from the two known human AIDS viruses. If the virus had jumped from monkeys to humans in recent times, as some have suggested, the viruses would be identical or nearly so. The findings appear in Thursday's issue of the British scientific journal Nature.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-ANTIBODIES</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers studying four AIDS-infected men who appeared to stop producing detectable antibodies to the disease said the virus may have stopped reproducing in those patients. Tests to pinpoint AIDS are based upon detection of the antibodies produced by the body to fight the virus. But <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Saah </PERSON>, epidemiology professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, said the findings do not imply increased dangers of blood supply contamination, since the instances of AIDS victims who stop producing detectable antibodies to the disease are `` very, very rare.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-HOTLINE</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An AIDS hotline has expanded from 130 operators to 220 to accommodate a rush of calls generated in part by a government educational pamphlet `` Understanding AIDS'' mailed to 10 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> homes, officials said. The 24-hour hotline, 1-800-342-AIDS, offers referrals in English and Spanish for people seeking help in their areas for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Officials expect 2 million calls in 1988.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS-SCIENCE ACADEMY</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> committee on AIDS said federal legislation shielding carriers of the virus from discrimination is crucial to fighting the epidemic. The report also said the hundreds of thousands of Americans unknowingly infected with the virus should be considered as suffering from the disease even if they do n't have full-scale AIDS. The panel said there is a growing consensus that `` the vast majority of persons'' with the virus `` will eventually progress to AIDS if no treatment is found to slow or halt the progression of the infection.'' The report called for development of federal standards for labs doing AIDS testing and recommended that AIDS testing be mandatory only in cases involving donations of blood or organs for transplant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
