<HEAD>City Meets Most Of Payroll, But Some City Employees Still Waiting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An infusion of state money enabled this financially strapped city to pay most of its 300 workers Wednesday, five days after their paychecks were due, the city's treasurer said But city Treasurer <PERSON> Charlotte </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said unless Mayor <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Officer </PERSON> authorized the transfer of additional funds into the city's general revenue account, about 30 city employees would not get paid for a few days more Officer was in a meeting and could not be reached for comment, his office said. On Wednesday morning, Mrs. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said, the town received its regular quarterly personal property tax payment from the state totaling $ 93,464. The payment supplemented money already on hand and allowed it to meet most of its $ 274,000 bimonthly payroll. But Mrs. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> still was $ 55,000 short of being able to pay all workers. `` We'll pay all police, all firefighters, all public works employees and then we'll go from there,'' she said. The checks were issued early in the afternoon, she said. The remaining employees might have to wait a few days for their paychecks until the city's regular state sales tax payment arrives, she said, unless the mayor authorizes the transfer of motor fuel tax funds into the payroll account, a move that a state official said could jeopardize future state support. Employees in this <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> town of 55,000 were supposed to be paid this past Friday. It was the second time in less than a month that paychecks were delayed. Though Officer could not be reached by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, he told the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday that there was enough money in the city's various bank accounts to cover the paychecks _ if the treasurer would cooperate and issue the checks. He did not elaborate. Officer contended that the late paychecks were `` an unfortunate situation that is not necessary'' and blamed Mrs. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, contending that she was angry because her entire staff was laid off in April to help save money. Mrs. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> countered that Officer was upset because she was enforcing sound accounting policies. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Klohr </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>, said that motor fuel tax funds could be used to pay city employees who do road work but not for other employees. A transfer of motor fuel funds for other workers would violate department guidelines, and the department could withhold future motor fuel tax payments, he said.
