<HEAD>Former Hostage Practices Urban Missionary Skills In Chicago</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Less than a year ago, <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> trudged through the rough terrain of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, a captive of rebel soldiers. Now, she's giving out food and clothing to desperate people in an urban ministry, in hopes of developing skills to use as a Christian missionary in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The 32-year-old <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> native, who went to <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> to teach English and work as a missionary, says the seven weeks she spent as a hostage are behind, but not forgotten. `` A lot of people do n't have certain freedoms and suffer a great deal. It's one thing to know about it cognitively, but it's another thing to experience a little of it yourself,'' Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said Wednesday. She was kidnapped last July 7. She and her three fellow hostages, including two Americans, were freed seven weeks later thanks to appeals from former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Kenyan governments, Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. After a 100-mile walk, they arrived safely in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> on Aug. 25. Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> remembers being roused from sleep in the middle of the night by soldiers who claimed they were `` saving our lives.'' The captors, members of the <ORGANIZATION> Sudanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, planned to attack the village and did not want the three `` caught in the cross-fire,'' Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. The Sudanese rebels have waged a five-year civil war against the government, which is dominated by Moslems from the predominantly <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> northern section of the country. The Sudanese <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is fighting for government reforms and autonomy for <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s three southern provinces, where most people are Christian or animist. After packing malaria medicine, some first-aid supplies, a Bible and a few other belongings, Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> was led out of the house she was living in at <ORGANIZATION> Bishop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gwynne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> near the southern Sudanese town of <LOCATION> Mundri </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said she and three other hostages were forced to walk through the countryside of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, the largest country in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. They slept on the side of the road or in rebel camps, ate sporadically, drank bad water and trudged through waterways, she recalled. `` Certain aspects of the physical parts were hard _ long walks and bad water,'' she said. `` But the psychological parts were hard, too ... not knowing how long we would be kept, not knowing what each day was going to bring.'' In October, Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to work with the <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION> providing emergency food, clothing and housing to poor people in the <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> neighborhood on the city's rough <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said she and four friends are volunteering in the urban mission as preparation for a missionary project they've been planning for more than a decade. The five _ a nurse, an architect, two teachers and a businessman-aviation mechanic _ plan to leave for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after another year of training and language classes in Spanish. `` Our commitment to the Lord is the underlying thing,'' she said. `` Everything is n't rosy, but there's a commitment underneath it _ ours is strong.'' Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Johnson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview Wednesday that the first thing her daughter wanted to do when she got home was eat broccoli. `` We really expected her to be different, but she was the same old <PERSON> Katie </PERSON>,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said.
