<HEAD>Train Collision Kills 2, Hurts 29 in Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A passenger express train going more than 70 mph rear-ended a sitting freight train Wednesday, killing two people and injuring as many as 29, a Dutch railway spokesman said. The four-car passenger train carrying about 60 passengers derailed and tumbled down an embankment after hitting the gravel-laden train in southwestern <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> at about 10:40 a.m., said spokesman <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Meijer </PERSON>. He said the 39-year-old locomotive engineer of the passenger train was killed, as was a 79-year-old Dutch woman, identified as <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sitter </PERSON>. <PERSON> Meijer </PERSON> said nine people were hospitalized, two in critical condition, and up to 20 others were treated for minor injuries. The lead passenger car was left with one end sticking up in the air, <PERSON> Meijer </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview from the railway's head office in this central Dutch city. He said the cause of the collision was not immediately known. The passenger train traveling at about 74 mph was bound from <LOCATION> Roosendaal </LOCATION>, a major junction in the southern <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> about 60 miles south of <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>, to <PERSON> Vlissingen </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Zeeland </LOCATION> province, the railway spokesman said. Visibility was good at the site of the accident between the stations of <LOCATION> Rilland-Bath </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Krabbendijke </PERSON>, where the double-track Roosendaal-Vlissingen main line runs in a slight bend, according to <PERSON> Meijer </PERSON>. He said the freight train was being used to try out a new energy conservation method and the gravel cars were hooked up to the electric engine as a simulated payload. The train was supposed to start and stop three times, he said, adding that it was not clear `` why the engineer of th