<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` flexible freeze'' plan to end the federal budget deficit by 1993 depends on an optimistic outlook and a reduction in interest rates by at least 2 percentage points, his economic advisers said Wednesday. `` We all concluded that a flexible freeze is the right way to go, that is indeed doable,'' said former Deputy Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ended four days of private talks with <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leaders and advisers at his seaside vacation retreat. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would contrast his plan to the `` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> mirage'' of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a slap at the Democratic front-runner's references to a `` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> miracle'' of home-state revival while he has been governor. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan also depends on a reduction in the budget deficit that is occurring anyway and a fast-rising surplus in the nation's Social Security trust fund, the consultants said The vice president has said he would reduce the deficit by the end of a first term by freezing most spending and without raising any taxes. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>, who quit his job as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s chief economist in 1985 because his advocacy of a tax increase was at odds with White House policy, told reporters he was a convert to the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal. If <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is elected, financial markets will rally on the assumption that the deficit will be attacked seriously, <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON> suggested. `` The markets will respond and bring down interest rates another notch, 2 percentage points, and that will get us down and get us within inches of budget balance in 1993,'' said <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> economist. However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s declarations that he would reject the advice of a bipartisan commission studying the federal deficit if it should call for a tax increase drew skepticism on Wednesday from one of those he met with, Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Republican and a member of the blue-ribbon panel, said the commission's work would not be swayed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s comments `` We are not going to get involved in any presidential campaigns,'' <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON> told reporters during a picture-taking session Wednesday with the vice president. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> interrupted <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON> at one point, saying: `` I hope the commission listens a little bit to the American people in this election.'' `` That's what I think an election is about. The commission can take an objective look and come up with whatever it wants. I'd be much more persuaded by what the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people say.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, made up of appointees of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as well as members of both parties in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, was formed earlier this year to try to come up with a bipartisan package of deficit-reduction proposals. The panel, which will also include two members appointed by the new president-elect in November, will submit its report in 1989. Democratic critics, as well as many private economists, argue that it is unlikely the budget deficit, $ 150 billion last year, can be eliminated without some form of new taxes. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal calls for a `` flexible freeze'' that would keep overall spending except for Social Security payments at levels in the budget approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for fiscal year 1989, plus inflation. The freeze would be flexible because some spending could go up, but increases would have to be offset by identical reductions in other areas. So far, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has not provided details on which programs he would like to cut and which ones he would like to see expanded. The vice president, who has clinched the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nomination, has also proposed a reduction in the tax on capital gains _ profits from the sale of real estate, stocks or other assets _ to 15 percent from its current maximum of 28 percent. Many economists have suggested that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals would not go far enough in trimming the budget deficit. `` I'm not surprised that the Democrats would say that,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` All they want to do is spend and tax. There is no change I can see or hear out of the campaign that would lead you to believe anything other than that on the Democratic side.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> held two days of talks on economic issues on Tuesday and Wednesday. They followed similar discussions with outside advisers last Friday and Saturday on other domestic issues. He has been at his retreat overlooking the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> since last Thursday and will remain here until Friday, combining strategy and issues sessions with a vacation. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that the economists who advised him assured him that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy was strong. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that the Index of Leading Indicators, a major guage of the country's economic health, was up in April for the third consecutive month. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that none of the half dozen private economists visiting him foresaw a recession in the coming months. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> who has frequently trumpted the 65-month economic expansion as a sign of success for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> economic policies _ policies he derided in 1980 as `` voodoo economics'' _ cautioned the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday not to do anything that would jeopardize that expansion.
