<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates for the homeless Wednesday criticized President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remarks at a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> news conference defending the nation's treatment of the homeless by citing the case of a street woman who fought <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s efforts to hospitalize her. They said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> inaccurately described the case of <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, the homeless woman who waged the much-publicized battle against the city. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remarks came in response to a reporter's suggestion that Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was not convinced by the president's statements that serious human rights deficiencies did not exist in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He said he wished <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would visit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> long enough to correct the `` mistaken view about the things that occasionally dominate the press, about prejudice, racial or religious, in our country, about people, the so-called street people who apparently have no place to live.'' `` But I do n't think he quite could understand a recent situation: a young lady living on the sidewalks of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, living out there on the sidewalk, winter and summer, and so for her own sake, the police picked her up to bring her to where she could be placed in a shelter and she took her case to court and won her case in court that she should be allowed to go back and sleep on the sidewalk where she had been because that's what she preferred to do. `` Well, when you have a free country, how far can we go in impinging on the freedom of someone who says this is the way I want to live? I think we could straighten him out if he saw what we did in our country.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, also known as <PERSON> Billie </PER