/PERSON> administration to provide meaningful programs.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, president of the Partnership for the Homeless, which operates shelters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and elsewhere, also decried <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s comments. `` The president's statement ... suggesting that the shameful problem of growing homelessness in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is the result of what he referred to as ` street people' who are homeless by choice totally ignores the fact that the vast majority of homelessness has been caused by his own policies which have gutted the principal federal programs to provide affordable housing for low-income and moderate-income people,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` The most authoritative national survey of 47 of our largest cities shows that less than 7 percent of the homeless are so by choice and most homeless are members of families who simply can not find affordable housing.'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrahams </PERSON>, associate director of the Coalition for the Homeless in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, agreed that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had misrepresented the homeless problem. Many of the homeless are families, he said; he estimated there were 750,000 homeless children, and their average age is 6. `` If Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was to visit this country, he would n't be here long before he saw homeless people. He would see them at <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, where he might arrive; he would see them living across the street from the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, where he would be greeted,'' <PERSON> Abrahams </PERSON> said.
