<HEAD>NBC President Warns Broadcast Rules Hampering Networks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government regulation is hobbling the three major television broadcast networks in the face of unregulated competition from the cable industry, the president of top-rated <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. `` Given the economics of the network business today, the depressing fact is that you have to be the first-place network to keep your head above water, because second - or third-place does n't do it for you anymore,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said in a speech to representatives of the cable and broadcast `` And without some new sources of income, the future of the networks, to put it charitably, is uncertain,'' he said. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, the prime-time leader, is in a better financial position than <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> because of `` a few more hit shows than the other guys have and a gentleman named <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON>, who can not be expected to carry us over the top forever.'' The Cosby Show is one of TV's top-rated shows. The <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> president said the networks are being hamstrung by outdated federal regulations that bar the networks from having a financial interest in programs produced by others and limit what they can produce themselves. The government also prohibits the networks from owning cable systems, syndicating programs domestically and sharing in the profits of syndication of shows produced by network-owned stations. Supplying cable programming and operating cable networks are two of the few opportunities available to the networks to broaden their business bases, he said. `` We can do in cable what we ca n't do in broadcasting,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told reporters after his speech. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> last month announced that it had agreed to buy the <ORGANIZATION> Tempo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> cab