<HEAD>Hutton Investigator Says He Couldn't Find Guilt in Top Management</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Attorney General <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> testified Wednesday that his private investigation of check kiting at <PERSON> E.F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> did n't fault senior management because he could n't find evidence of wrongdoing at the top. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, sued for defamation for identifying a former <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> branch manager as a wrongdoer in a 1985 report, stoutly defended the investigation his <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> law firm conducted after <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> pleaded guilty to 2,000 mail and wire fraud charges. `` I thought I could catch a high person, but I never could,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said. Though he was suspicious that top officials were aware of illegal overdrafting practices, <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said he found no evidence of intentional wrongdoing by senior executives. `` I'm not going to put my name on something charging somebody with wrongdoing if they ... did not have the intent to do something wrong,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> testified in the federal court trial of the case brought by former <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> branch manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON>, now a <LOCATION> Sarasota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, businessman, claims <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> negligently ignored evidence that cash management practices that led to <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>'s guilty plea were approved by top executives. <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON>, who ran <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> branches in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, alleges that <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s report put false blame on him and the eight other branch and regional officials who were identified as initiating illegal overdrafting. But <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> `` never told me that anybody au