ng by top managers, he faulted senior executives for not properly monitoring the cash management procedures being followed at lower levels in the company. `` They did n't have any controls at all,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> testified. The company was `` just letting people go wild, doing whatever they wanted to do.'' The report recommended that <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morley </PERSON>, the `` money mobilizer'' who devised aggressive cash management systems, be relieved of any duties involving <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>'s banking activities. `` Everybody disowned Mr. <PERSON> Morley </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said. `` Nobody owned up that they had anything to do with him.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, executive vice president, was identified in the investigation as the company's chief financial officer and forced to resign for failing to maintain proper controls. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said his investigation had trouble identifying which top executive ultimately was responsible for the firm's financial procedures because `` nobody wanted to be known as the chief financial officer.'' Many overdrafting procedures used by large companies, including <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON>, are legal because the banks are aware of them, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> said. But he conceded in questioning by <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON>, that in the case of many <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> accounts, `` most banks, or many banks, did not know what was happening to them.'' `` My best information was they did not tell the banks, except in a few instances'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said.
