<HEAD>Family Honor At Heart of Bedouin Murder Conspiracy Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 3rd graf, `The Tarawnehs ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Bedouin couple demanded the death and mutilation of their unwanted son-in-law to avenge their honor, prosecutors said Wednesday, but the defense accused authorities of blowing up a tragic family problem into a murder conspiracy case. <PERSON> Suad </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ghada </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON>, now of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, are accused of plotting to kill their daughter's husband and his family because in 1986 the 17-year-old girl spurned a marriage they arranged, and instead married her Syrian cousin. The Tarawnehs asked a private detective, <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrillo </PERSON>, to cut off the son-in-law's finger and genitals and return them to the couple, along with color photos of the bodies, Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dimitrouleas </PERSON> said in his opening arguments. The alleged plot was stopped before anyone was hurt, but the parents were accused of murder conspiracy and solicitation to commit murder. The Tarawnehs were arrested last February in <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Petrillo </PERSON> contacted authorities about the case. `` ` I'd like to keep the photos of the body as a souvenir,''' Dimitrouleas quoted <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON> as saying on secretly recorded tapes. `` ` You're Italian, <PERSON> Petrillo </PERSON>, you understand family. You understand honor. That's why we asked you to help us.''' Dimitrouleas quoted <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON> as telling the detective `` We are Moslem, and when you are in the desert, honor is very important to you.'' The prosecutor took aim at defense contentions that the threats against the son-in-law were only empty words. He noted that the cautious <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON> had even called <PERSON> Petrillo </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION> because he did not want to use the word `` kill'' over the telephone. In his opening arguments, defense attorney <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Spadaro </PERSON> disputed the prosecution version, saying the Tarawnehs were not killers, but tragic victims wrapped up in the emotions of their family crisis and the father's drinking. `` The first tragedy was the drinking problem, the second was the loss of their daughter in 1986 and the third was the hiring of this investigator,'' said <PERSON> Spadaro </PERSON>. <PERSON> Petrillo </PERSON>, he said, had been hired to find the daughter and located her in nearby <LOCATION> Tamarac </LOCATION>. But when she refused to see her parents, the detective turned their angry initial reaction into a murder plot, <PERSON> Spadaro </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON>, 46, a gynecologist, and his wife, 44, a nurse, left <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> 18 years ago. When their daughter <PERSON> Raniah </PERSON> married her Syrian cousin <PERSON> Mouataz </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdulsalam </PERSON> in 1986 over their objections, the angered parents said their honor had been blackened and had to be avenged. <PERSON> Abdulsalam </PERSON> is the son of Mrs. <PERSON> Tarawneh </PERSON>'s sister. The daughter testified Wednesday that her father once sent her uncle to kill her in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, and had tried to cut off her hand when she first told him she wanted to marry her cousin. He also had her jailed briefly on what she said were trumped-up charges of stealing her mother's jewelry. `` He said I'd regret it, he'd kill me, he'd kill my husband, that I would regret it for the rest of my life,'' she testified. But, she said, he also wrote her a card apologizing, saying `` I never meant to hurt you _ you are my blood and flesh.'' She said her father abused both alcohol and prescription drugs, and had lost jobs at hospitals because of his habits. At first the Tarawnehs planned to kidnap their daughter and sell her into a prostitution ring in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, but that fell through and they switched to the murder plot, according to investigator <PERSON