<FIRST>r a AM-LeadWater     06-01 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lead Water,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Lead Concentrations in School Water Violates EPA
Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city shipped bottled water to half of its elementary schools Wednesday after state health officials found lead concentrations in drinking water exceeded federal limits. Officials also plan to test schools outside the city following a report that drinking water in 40 <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> grade schools is unsafe and that water in another 19 schools contained lead levels just below <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> limits, said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Prothrow-Stith </PERSON>, state public health commissioner. `` Obviously there is a problem and there's going to have to be more testing to insure that the public health and welfare is protected,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keough </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> deputy regional administrator. `` We are concerned because some of the levels were very high.'' Some parents gave their children bottles of water to take Wednesday, and school officials said they were concerned about the dangers of extended consumption of lead-tainted water for the city's 30,000 students in pre-kindergarten through fifth grade. `` This is another situation where urban schools are left behind,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ubinas </PERSON>, principal of the <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blackstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in the city's <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION>. `` Now we not only have to deal with the drug problem and the traffic outside but the lead. When will we be allowed to educate?'' The state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> sampled water at 79 public and two private elementary schools over the Memorial Day weekend after a television station reported high lead content at eight schools. Water at 40 schools exceeded the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> limit of 50 parts per million of lead in drinking water. The tests revealed a level of 2,300 parts per million at the water supply source in one school and 1,400 ppm at a water fountain in another. <PERSON> Keough </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in July plans to recommend reducing the unsafe lead content level to 20 ppm. The tests showed an additional 19 schools had lead concentrations of between 20 and 50 ppm. Lead poisoning attacks the brain, kidneys, nervous system and red blood cells and can lead to brain damage and death, health officials said. Lead occurs in food, air, soil, dust, paint and water. Officials said poisoning is rarely caused by contaminated water alone, but overexposure to lead can stunt physical and mental development in children, causing nervous disorders, learning disabilities and mental problems. Children under 8 are especially vulnerable, they added. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Timperi </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, which analyzed the water samples, said three likely sources for the lead are lead pipes, lead solder used from 1980-86 and electric cooling systems in water fountains. Some lead pipes in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> schools are more than 50 years old, he said. Schools are more susceptible to high lead levels because water sits in pipes after school and on weekends, allowing greater lead absorption. In a 1976 study, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> found that 25 percent of Boston-area households exceeded federal lead safety limits. <PERSON> Keough </PERSON> said officials will attack the problem on a `` fountain by fountain'' basis by repairing or replacing pipes, solder and cooling systems. The <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> Wednesday delivered 680 five-gallon bottles of water, 136 coolers and 272,000 paper cups to city schools, Great Bear sales manager <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Pires-Donaghy </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
