<FIRST>r a AM-BroadwaySeason     06-01 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Broadway Season,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broadway Season Ends With Box Office and Attendance Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business boomed on Broadway during the 1987-88 season with a record $ 253 million worth of tickets sold to more than 8.1 million theatergoers, the League of American Theaters and Producers announced Wednesday. The figures solidified the upturn in ticket sales that began during the previous season when grosses totaled $ 209 million and some 7 million people saw a Broadway show, the league said. But while the grosses and attendance were up, production was down, with only 32 shows opening on Broadway between June 1, 1987 and May 29, 1988, compared to 40 the previous season. Still, the shows that managed to get to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> during the 1987-88 survived longer. `` There's a lot of choice on Broadway which is probably why there are so many people going,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, director of research for the league. `` We sold almost 200,000 tickets in each of the last three weeks. That's about as good as it ever gets.'' Musicals, particularly `` The Phantom of the Opera,'' again dominated the year, but several plays were also very strong at the box office. `` Phantom,'' which had a record $ 19 million advance sale, is expected to have as long a life in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as such hardy holdovers from other seasons as `` Les Miserables,'' `` Cats,'' `` 42nd Street'' and `` A Chorus Line.'' There were 12 new musicals on Broadway during the 1987-88 season, compared to 11 the previous year. Although `` Phantom'' was the season's biggest musical hit, several other musicals were popular including `` Sarafina!,'' a South African musical; `` Chess,'' the <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice-ABBA-Trevor </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> extravaganza about international chess matches, and `` Into the <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>,'' a fairy tale musical written by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapine </PERSON>. Of the season's six revivals, the most successful was the Lincoln Center revival of <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>'s `` Anything Goes.'' There were eight new plays on Broadway, down from 13 the previous season, but of the eight, only one _ `` Serious Money'' _ was a quick flop. Five others are still running including the four <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> nominees for best play _ `` A Walk in the Woods'' by <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Blessing </PERSON>, `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s Come and Gone'' by <PERSON> August </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, `` M. Butterfly'' by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hwang </PERSON> and `` Speed-the-Plow'' by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>. `` How many seasons have there been where a show like ` Burn This' would not be nominated for best play? <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> said, referring to the season's fifth new play still running. `` In that sense, I think it was a rich season.'' If box office receipts were up, so were costs and ticket prices as well as risks to producers. The $ 50 ticket for a musical is now the norm rather than the exception. A $ 40 top ticket for a play on weekend nights is also not unusual. The average paid admission, according to the league, was $ 31.10, up from $ 29.86 for the previous season. The flops were more costly too. `` Carrie,'' a musical based on the <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> horror novel, lost a record $ 8 million and closed after five performances, the most expensive failure in Broadway history. <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> looks for the increase in ticket sales to continue. `` In terms of attendance, I think we will do very well because the last three weeks have been extraordinary,'' he said. `` We have the momentum to keep going. A lot of that may be from tourism and the weakness of the dollar. The pick up we usually get from tourism during the summer is happening earlier.''
