<HEAD>Residents Move Back After Rains, Broken Dam Force Evacuation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMANCHE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Heavy thunderstorms dumped more than 10 inches of rain on this north-central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> town, overflowing a creek, obliterating an earthen dam and forcing the evacuation of about 60 people early Wednesday, authorities said. The storm waters also damaged homes, businesses and bridges and briefly shut down some highways elsewhere in the area late Tuesday and early Wednesday. `` A wall of water came through here and these people barely got out in time,'' said <PERSON> Gayle </PERSON> <PERSON> Godfrey </PERSON> as he stood amid torn furnishings and soggy carpet drying on the shore of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eans </LOCATION>. The flood's apex came between 3 a.m. and 6 a.m., and by 8:30 a.m., residents were allowed to return to their homes. All that remained of the former 100-acre private lake at daylight were acres of mud, tons of debris and fallen trees. <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> <PERSON> Godfrey </PERSON> pointed to grass and mud stains 4 -LCB- feet high on the white walls of her home, which she estimated sustained about $ 30,000 in damage. `` We had to leave out the back door when the water came pouring in,'' she said. `` We've lived here 22 years, and it's never gotten this high before.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Godfrey </PERSON>, 40, and her 18-year-old son, <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, ran up a hill to the home of a neighbor. From the top of the hill, she said she heard a loud roar about 5 a.m. as water broke through the dam that was built in the 1930s in a water reclamation project. Floodwaters also overflowed the banks of <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, tearing through homes and businesses in Comanche and knocking chunks of pavement from bridgets. `` I looked outside my trailer house to see how the rain was and saw water flowing over my tires,'' said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON>, who evacuated his home about 4 a.m. `` My parents came over in a four-wheel drive and got me. A fire truck came into the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> area later and evacuated everybody else. `` At the trailer house across the street, they had to get a boat to find that man. Water was chest-high in his house,'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> said. At <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Comanche </LOCATION>, about four miles southeast of this town of 12,600, a dam held but water spilled over its lip, said <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogle </PERSON>, a teacher at <ORGANIZATION> Comanche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, where the evacuated residents stayed until the floodwaters subsided. North along <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 377, the floodwaters blocked several underpasses and bridges with logs and debris. The driver of an 18-wheeler reportedly swam to safety as floodwaters washed his truck off the road. Streets in several other counties in the area also were flooded by the storms, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported. Comanche and 42 other <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> counties, most of them in the north-central part of the state, remained under a severe thunderstorm watch until late Wednesday night.
