<FIRST>r i AM-US-PoorNations     06-01 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poor Nations,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Will Support Help with Debts of `Poorest' Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said Wednesday it supports granting concessions to some of the world's poorest nations to make it easier for them repay billions of dollars in loans. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told a news conference at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> that lower interest rates or more liberal terms of repayment could help ease the pressure on those countries. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said members of the <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> _ a group of lenders including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ should be able to negotiate their own terms of financing. `` It is important to realize that what we are talking about here is a change in the policy of the <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, which would permit creditor governments to differentiate in the approach to rescheduling,'' he said. Concessions would involve only `` official debt owed by the poorest of the poor,'' he said. Most of the money owed by the poorest countries is `` official debt'' _ funds lent by developed countries. Many African nations can not repay foreign debts that now exceed $ 200 billion for the continent and have urged Western nations to write off part or all the obligation. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> made clear he does not propose that kind of relief. He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal `` will continue to require that each country be looked at on a case-by-case basis. It is therefore not a call for a generalized debt relief proposal or a global approach, if you will. But it does represent a change, it certainly does, as far as official debt owed by the poorest of the poor.'' In effect, this means the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will not block efforts by the other <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> member countries to draw up debt concession agreements with certain countries. Asked if other members of the Club of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> are likely to favor his proposal, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said: `` I think it is a major step in the direction of some suggestions that have been heretofore made by some of our <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> partners. So I believe they will welcome this.'' `` Those governments that felt free, legally or from a policy basis, to grant concessional or perhaps more concessional interest rates would be free to do so, whereas other governments could perhaps look at a broader range of maturities as a means of contributing,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration does not have the authority to write off debt. `` One of the difficulties ... the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has with a proposal to move to concessional interest rates on official debt is that that constitutes to a degree debt forgiveness, which the executive branch is not empowered, alone, to grant,'' he said. `` We are permitted to negotiate more liberal terms of repayment. We have been doing that, and my remarks indicate a willingness on our part to consider moving along that same path in the future,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said.
