<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said Wednesday its chief economic forecasting gauge rose a modest 0.2 percent in April, an increase analysts said signaled continued healthy economic growth for the rest of this presidential election year. It marked the third consecutive monthly increase in the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Index of Leading Indicators, following an identical 0.2 percent rise in March and a giant 1.5 percent February surge, which had been the largest gain in more than two years. In other good news for the economy, the government reported that orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for manufactured goods shot up 1.2 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted $ 218.7 billion following an even bigger 1.6 percent March increase, indicating that industrial production will be increasing during the months ahead.
