<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ten Years Later, More Blacks Embrace Mormon Faith</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Ten years ago, the Mormon Church began admitting
blacks to its priesthood. While its missionaries have achieved
remarkable success in Africa and elsewhere abroad, at home they
labor to dispel the bitter legacy of 130 years of racial exclusion.
   ___</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mormon elder <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> today guides his white brethren through sacred temple rituals that just a decade ago were denied him because of his black skin. `` I think I have been greatly blessed. I feel my life has been very much fulfilled,'' said <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, who twice monthly performs rites in the church's <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Temple </LOCATION>. `` I may never be a rich man, but I do n't care to be. The riches I have are to have a good family, to teach my children the gospel.'' The ban ended June 9, 1978, when the late church President <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimball </PERSON> announced he'd received a revelation from God opening the priesthood, held by all worthy Mormon males older than 11, to black members of The Church of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> of Latter-day <ORGANIZATION> Saints </ORGANIZATION>. But despite the church's startling success among blacks since then, particularly in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, it still labors at home to overcome the ban's legacy: a lingering perception that Mormonism is a faith for whites. The church numbers 8,500 members in <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and 5,000 in <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> and is growing by about 2,000 converts a year in each country. New missions have opened recently in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leone </LOCATION>. In predominantly black <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, the church reaps more than 70 converts monthly. Blacks in the American South hold leadership positions once open only to whites. `` I started out being exotic and ended up being generic,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cherry </PERSON>, one of the few American blacks baptized before 1978. Nor does the legacy of the ban appear to have slowed the church's overall growth. Since 1978, the church says its membership has nearly doubled from 3.8 million to 6.5 million worldwide. Black members say deliberate racism is extremely rare among white Mormons. Rather, they say, blacks and whites struggle with cultural and economic barriers that can undermine the most sincere fellowships. `` The first question I get is, ` Where did you play ball?''' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a black employed in the church's public communications department. `` When I say I did n't, then in their minds I'm either a pimp or a drug dealer. I'm still struggling with people who wo n't accept me for who I am, but I wo n't let that affect my beliefs.'' Like many black Mormons, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is skeptical of the church's claim of a divine origin for the doctrine `` I choose to look at it as something that man placed and God removed,'' he said, echoing a view shared by independent Mormon scholars and at least one high-ranking church official. The late <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a member of the Council of the Twelve and a counselor to former church President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, never accepted the ban as doctrine and nearly engineered its reversal, said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s grandson, <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Firmage </PERSON>. Ten members of the Twelve, which assists the governing First Presidency, voted to lift the ban in 1969. <PERSON> Firmage </PERSON> said the vote was nullified when the council's senior active member, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, returned to town. Little evidence indicates the policy originated with church founder <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>; it was not among the dozens of written revelations he left before his 1844 assassination in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. As articulated by <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s successor, <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION>, the ban was rooted in the belief that black Africans were descendants of the biblical Cain, cursed by <PERSON> God </PERSON> for murdering his brother, <PERSON> Abel </PERSON>. Church leaders in 1969 reiterated the policy was divine doctrine taught by <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and every succeeding Mormon prophet, but by 1978, months before the ban's demise, they were saying that only God knew the reason why. A decade later, that apparently remains the official view. Elder <PERSON> Dallin </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oaks </PERSON>, a member of the Twelve, said in an interview that theological arguments trying to buttress the doctrine were largely speculative. God does n't give reasons for his revelations, he said. `` We can put reason to revelation. We can put reasons to commandments. When we do, we're on our own. Some people put reasons to the one we're talking about here and they turned out to be spectacularly wrong,'' <PERSON> Oaks </PERSON> said. Mormons define priesthood as the authority to act in the name of God, and membership is a prerequisite to any appointment in the church's lay leadership or to performing such rites as baptism, temple marriage and healing the sick. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, for instance, was not permitted to bless his infant sons before <PERSON> Kimball </PERSON>'s revelation. A white member of the priesthood gave the blessings instead. `` There were restrictions which, in a worldly sense, were hard to accept,'' said <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, who two days after the ban was lifted became the first black ordained to the faith's priesthood since the faith's infancy, when at least two blacks held priesthood offices. Among Africans, the restriction appears to have made less difference. `` They do n't seem to take it the way I think I would if I had been involved,'' said <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> <PERSON> Clegg </PERSON>, a missionary in <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> in the early 1980s. As early as 1946 the church was receiving inquiries from Nigerians who had read church missionary tracts or articles. The Nigerian government, however, refused to admit missionaries until the policy was dropped. The appeal of Mormonism also spread to <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>. When missionaries arrived in the two countries, they were greeted by thousands eager for baptism. Among American blacks, memories of the ban haunt missionary efforts. But black and white Mormons alike say economic and social barriers are more divisive than church doctrine. `` I would say that where you have black middle-class converts coming into middle-class congregations, the prognosis is good,'' said <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> Mauss </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> sociologist who has monitored the progress of black Mormons. `` Where you have lower-class blacks being converted to middle-class congregations, that's not good.'' <PERSON> Mauss </PERSON> cited surveys taken from 1972 to 1985 by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that suggested white Mormons were slightly more tolerant of blacks than non-Mormon whites. But when racial tensions flare, they take their toll of fledgling black converts alreay sensitive to the church's image among non-Mormon friends and relatives. In <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, black baptisms averaged six to 12 a month in the early 1980s, but a majority fell away after racial incidents, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON>, a black who sits on the high council of the <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION> Stake, or diocese. Among those who left the church was <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON>'s wife, taunted with epithets by 11-year-olds she was teaching in Primary, the church's organization for children `` A very few whites, two or three, were still prejudiced and they let the blacks know it. It made the rest of the whites feel bad because the blacks were judging the church by them,'' said <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON>, a member of eight years. Worried at the erosion among black converts, local leaders offered them a choice, to continue attending mixed congregations or form their own with black leaders. They unanimously picked the latter. Since then, the number of active black participants has risen from about 50 to more than 200.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, June 6</NOTE>
