<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices shot up in a post-holiday weekend buying spree that pushed up the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average nearly 75 points. Analysts could not point to any specific developments to account for Tuesday's rally, but they said sentiment seemed to have grown that interest rates are near a peak for the time being. The Dow industrials rose 74.68 points to close at 2,031.12. That was the widely followed barometer's best gain since a 76.42 rise on Jan. 4 and the sixth biggest increase ever.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New-home sales climbed 4 percent in April to the highest level in a year, the government said, but analysts said rising interest rates would likely dampen sales this summer. New single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 679,000 last month, the fastest pace since new homes sold at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> departments said in a joint report Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contracting for new construction projects declined 6 percent in April from the previous month, extending a downward slide that began last fall, a report said. The survey, released Tuesday by the F.W. Dodge Division of <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, estimated the annualized value of all newly started construction projects in April at $ 226.97 billion, compared with $ 242.38 billion in March. F.W. <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON> said high vacancy rates in commercial properties, particularly offices and apartments, were responsible in reversing the industry's five-year upswing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices farmers got for raw products in May averaged 3.1 percent over April levels and were 4.7 percent over their mark for the same month last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Higher prices for hogs, oranges, soybeans and broilers were partially offset by lower prices for tomatoes, onions, milk and upland cotton,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in its preliminary report Tuesday. May farm commodity prices averaged 134 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures. A year ago the index was 128.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses dropped 22 percent to $ 30.5 billion in 1987, the first dip since 1983 in the rush by overseas investors to acquire American assets, the government said. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that foreigners spent $ 39.2 billion to acquire or establish businesses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1986, compared with $ 23.1 billion in 1985 and $ 15.2 billion in 1984.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a victory for bargain hunters and discount dealers, upheld federal regulations that allow a multibillion-dollar `` gray market'' in which costly imported goods are sold at reduced prices. The justices, voting 5-4 Tuesday, said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> does not have to shut down the gray market _ famous-name, foreign-made goods bearing valid <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trademarks sold in this country without approval from trademark owners.
