<HEAD>Macmillan Restructuring Could Leave Room for Bid by Bass, Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s new billion-dollar restructuring plan, designed to thwart a hostile takeover bid by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, leaves the door open for higher bids from Bass or other potential suitors, some analysts believe. The venerable publishing giant announced Tuesday that its board of directors had adopted a plan to split the company's publishing and non-publishing operations into two separate, publicly owned corporations and to pay special dividends to shareholders. <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> valued the dividends and securities to be paid under the restructuring plan at more than $ 64 a share, or over $ 1.66 billion. Some analysts who follow the company estimated the plan would be worth $ 65 to $ 70 a share. <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, who leads a group of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investors that launched a bid for <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> in mid-May, offered $ 64 a share for <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION>'s roughly 26 million outstanding shares The bid by the Bass group _ which holds 9.1 percent of the company's shares _ was rejected as inadequate by <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s board. The investor group had no comment on <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s restructuring proposal, said <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, an attorney at the law firm <ORGANIZATION> Kelly </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Hallman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, that is representing the group. The proposed restructuring still leaves room for Bass and other potential suitors to bid for <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>, but makes the possibility of an offer being supported by management more remote, said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorp </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Provident </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` This really puts pressure on -LRB- potential suitors -RRB- for time,'' <PERSON> Thorp </PERSON> said. Other possible bidders cited by market watchers are competitors <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> media tycoon <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>. Bass is keenly interested in <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s information services business, the company's fastest-growing and most profitable area, according to analysts. The business, which publishes reference books such as Who's Who and trade guides for lawyers, had sales of $ 229 million in 1987 _ up from $ 146 million two years before. Under the restructuring plan, the two new companies would be called <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION>, now a subsidiary of the parent, would be `` spun off'' as a dividend to shareholders For each share of existing <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> stock, shareholders would receive a cash dividend of $ 52.35, a half-share of common stock in the new <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION>, and $ 4.50 principal amount of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> subordinated debentures. The cash dividend of $ 52.35 consists of $ 25.20 from <ORGANIZAT