<SECOND>PM-Stocks-Rally, Bjt,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Scramble to Explain Reasons for Latest Stock Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market broke out of its May doldrums with a buying spree that carried the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average to its second biggest gain of the year. But analysts were hard-pressed to come up with an explanation for Tuesday's surge, which came on the heaviest daily volume since late January. `` Sometimes it's better just to enjoy and not analyze things like this,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a portfolio strategist for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's been a bad May.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DaPuzzo </PERSON>, manager of retail equity trading for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the warm weather over the Memorial Day holiday may have brightened investors' outlooks and prompted them to put some cash to work. `` You've got to start a summer rally sometime, and Memorial Day is usually the threshold to the summer,'' he said. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 74.68 on Tuesday to 2,031.12, its highest level since it closed at 2,036.31 on May 4. It was the biggest one-day advance in the market's most widely-followed index since a 76.42-point gain on Jan. 4, the first trading day of the year, and the sixth biggest rise ever. The gain in the Dow Jones industrials was so strong that a voluntary limit on computerized program trading was triggered when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION>'s rise swept past 50 points in the last hour of trading. But even after the so-called `` collar'' went into effect for the rest of the day, the blue-chip average extended its gain. It was the third time the collar had gone into effect since it was adopted in the aftermath of the Oct. 19 market crash in a bid to curb market volatility. Gainers outpaced losers by nearly 4 to 1 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 1,211 up, 333 down and 401 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> came to 247.61 million shares, up from 133.59 million in the previous session and the highest since 275.25 million shares were traded there on Jan. 25. Two utility stocks with dividend deadlines approaching accounted for about 90 million shares of volume. Nonetheless, volume was up from the sluggish pace of recent weeks that has prompted speculation that brokerage firms may resort to a round of layoffs. Analysts had been saying that the slow pace of trading reflected investors' uncertainty about the implications of continued strength in the economy. While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits, some investors worried that it could also reignite inflation and prompt the <ORGANIZATION> Fdederal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to choke it off by encouraging higher interest rates. Even as stock prices and trading volume swelled on Tuesday, some potential ingredients for a new surge in inflation were evident. Commodity futures prices surged, propelling a key inflation indicator, the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>'s index of 21 commodities, to a three-year high. But that failed to dampen enthusiasm in the stock market. Analysts said stock traders were heartened by the dollar's continuing stability and the bond market's resilience in the face of rising commodity prices Recent declines in bond prices have pushed their yields higher and made them more competitive with stocks for investors' money. They also cited relief that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> failed to boost its discount rate _ its interest charge on loans to financial institutions _ as some feared it would after the markets closed last week. <PERSON> Eldon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimm </PERSON>, a senior vice president at the brokerage Birr, <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said there is `` an enormous amount of cash around out of the market'' due to wariness in the wake of last October's crash. `` But every time we get a little rally going, people think they will miss the boat and buy something,'' he said.
