<HEAD>Attendants' Shortage Cancels USAir Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> said normal flight schedules would resume today after numerous holiday weekend flights were canceled when flight attendants refused to work end-of-the-month overtime to protest an impasse in contract negotiations. The airline, based at <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, canceled about two dozen of its 1,600 flights Tuesday, said spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based airline also canceled one flight Saturday, 81 on Sunday and 61 on Memorial Day. `` It's a very, very small percentage of the total,'' <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said. `` There's not chaos at the airports.'' <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said flight attendants' overtime is governed by federal regulations that limit them to 85 hours per month. He said flight attendants may fly five extra hours per month as overtime at the request of airlines, but they are not required to do so. Since today is the first day of the new month, the flight attendants would revert to their normal work schedules. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> has yet to complete an agreement for a new contract and seniority list with its flight attendants and those employed by <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> acquired last year and merged into its system on April 9. `` Apparently there is -LRB- a protest -RRB-, but it's not a union-organized protest. I think it's a spontaneous protest. I was as surprised as anyone else,'' said <PERSON> Juliette </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenoir </PERSON>, vice president of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based union and a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> flight attendant. `` My best sense is that flight attendants are just very upset at this whole issue of pay parity for the former <ORGANIZATION> PSA </ORGANIZATION> flight attendants. That may have been the straw that broke the camel's back,'' she said Ms. <PERSON> Lenoir </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> also has been asking attendants to do more work, such as serving travelers before takeoff, without a raise in pay since at least 1985. <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said most passengers booked on the canceled flights switched to other <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> flights or to other airlines. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s central operating hub is Greater <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>.
