<HEAD>Report Says Traders Raked In Big Profits Despite Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Floor brokers on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> posted their best year ever in 1987 despite the slashing of stock prices during the October market crash, a published report said today. Quoting confidential exchange records, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said the 54 `` specialist'' firms collectively lost $ 166.7 million in October but still managed to post profits of $ 369.3 million before taxes for the year. Specialists are appointed by the exchange to make markets in individual stocks. They are charged with making sure that market is orderly, even if it means buying and selling equities from their own accounts. They have been criticized for not doing more to smoothe out the market during the crash, but specialist advocates have commended their performance during the crisis. Financial data on specialists are kept secret and are not reported to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> because they are private enterprises, the paper said. The Times said it obtained the data from <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> staff sources who received the confidential records from the exchange as part of a continuing investigation into the crash. According to figures provided to the Times, specialists earned $ 1.85 billion before taxes from 1981 through 1987 while their equity capital amounted to $ 923 million at the end of last year. The Times said that indicates they took out of their businesses $ 1.38 billion, not including salaries and expenses. Specialists' returns have not dipped below 30 percent this decade, the paper said. Meanwhile, exchange members who deal with the public and are not specialists had capital of about $ 22.9 billion last year, but their pre-tax return amounted to 4.8 percent, the paper reported. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Grasso </PERSON>, president-elect of the exchange, noted that several new rules have been instituted to boost slightly the capital specialists must have on hand. He told the Times the earnings figures should have been lower because they did not take into account payments partners in the specialist firms made to themselves as a return on their investments.
