<HEAD>Counseling Helps Workers Prepare for Life After Layoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> is urging soon-to-be-laid-off <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> workers to do as he says and as he did _ stop using credit cards and pay off all the debts they can while they're still working <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> prepared for his layoff two years ago by paying off $ 3,000 in bills in one month so he would n't end up `` hitting the wall'' _ losing his home or other possessions after layoff benefits run out. `` I knew it was easier to pay them off when I was working 11 -LCB- - hour days than after I was laid off,'' said <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, who was recalled in May and is using his experience at the UAW-GM Crisis Center <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> counsels laid-off <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> workers who already have hit the wall. But <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and local agencies including <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counseling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> also are trying to teach workers how to avoid it. About 8,500 Pontiac-area workers are on layoff or will be by 1990, a portion of more than 30,000 <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> workers whose jobs will disappear in closings of at least 16 plants nationwide. Among the advice they receive: Stop using credit cards and prepare a realistic budget that takes into account lower income while benefits are coming in and potentially drastic reductions in income afterward. The lessons are hard for some workers to learn, <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> said. Losing a job `` is a loss just like the other losses we acknowledge, like the loss of a loved one,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonz </PERSON>, employment projects coordinator for <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. Victims experience the same stages of grief _ denial, anger, depression and finally acceptance _ as with other major losses, she said. But with a job loss, `` people have a tendency not to reach out for help available to them. `` There is a desire to hide from the situation. They might bring in the mail, but they do n't really open up the bills. Imagination takes over and makes it seem a worse situation than it is,'' <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonz </PERSON> said. Laid-off workers have hit the wall if they are being threatened with foreclosure, eviction, repossession or bankruptcy. Some give up, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonz </PERSON> said. But many are directed to <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counseling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit counseling agency that provides free assessments. Giving up can lead to bankruptcy filings, as many as 50 percent of which are unnecessary, said <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counseling </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahey </PERSON>, citing a recent study by <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The study showed half of 1,199 bankruptcy petitions surveyed had no ability to repay debts; 20 percent could have paid all but mortgage debts in three years, and 25 percent could have repaid 75 percent of their debts in three years, <PERSON> Leheay </PERSON> said. `` Once filed, a bankruptcy stays on the credit record for 10 years and indefinitely for life insurance policies and mortgage credit requests,'' she said.
