<HEAD>Help-Wanted Advertising Steady in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Help-wanted advertising, an indication of the demand for labor, held steady in April, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. The Board's Help-Wanted index, unchanged from the previous month, measures the volume of classified advertising in 51 major newspapers nationwide. But trends in the labor market continue to confound experts. `` While help-wanted advertising volume has shown no significant strength since last November, employment continues to rise,'' noted <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported April's unemployment rate was 5.4 percent, down from 5.6 percent in March. `` The best odds still favor a slowing of employment growth in the coming months, rather than a spurt in want-ad volume,'' he said. Advertising volume rose in five of the nine geographic regions measured, with the East South Central region posting the largest gain of 5.5 percent. It was followed by the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, where help-wanted advertising rose 2.9 percent, and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> region, up 1.7 percent. The <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> region registered the greatest decline of 5.8 percent.
