<HEAD>US Firms Continue To Attract Foreign Buyers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American businesses continue to attract high levels of foreign investment, in part because of the cheaper dollar and favorable <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic conditions, the government says. Foreigners spent $ 30.5 billion in 1987 to acquire or establish businesses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. That was down 22 percent from the record $ 39.2 billion in 1986, but nearly four times greater than the 1983 level of $ 8.1 billion. The driving force behind the big jump in foreign investment has been this country's huge trade deficit, which hit a record $ 171.2 billion last year. Foreigners have looked for ways to invest their dollars, earned through sales to Americans. As a consequence, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has moved from the world's largest creditor to the world's largest debtor. The report identified four factors that made <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses attractive to foreigners last year: _ The continued depreciation of the dollar encouraged foreign companies to shift operations to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> so that their expenses as well as sales were paid in dollars _ Moderate inflation and an expanding economy made prospects for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses look good _ Continuing takeover activity created opportunities for purchases _ And, fear that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would enact legislation to restrict imports likely motivated foreign companies to produce in, rather than export to, this country Analysts read little significance into the decline from 1986, cautioning that tax law changes and other factors may have held down the reported number for 1987. `` Everybody was trying to close deals in 1986 because of tax considerations, so it's quite possible that 1986 just borrowed some sales from 1987,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Herr </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analyst, said if past years are any guide, the 1987 total will be revised upward by 10 percent or more as additional deals are reported to the government. The 1986 figure had originally been reported at $ 31.5 billion, nearly 20 percent less than the revised figure released Tuesday. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said foreign investment would likely increase again in 1988 because of the continued fall of the dollar, which has lost about half of its value since 1985 as measured against the Japanese yen. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> right now looks like a very competitive place to produce. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies, especially when you look at them in yen terms, look very cheap and you're going to see continued strong buying,'' he said. Foreigners also have been buying corporate bonds, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> notes, stocks and other investments that do not show up in the report released Tuesday. It tracks money spent to establish new businesses or purchase a 10 percent or greater stake in existing companies. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses acquired or established by foreigners in 1987 employed 346,000 workers and owned 316,000 acres of land. The report showed that <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was the largest purchaser at $ 11.5 billion, up from $ 8.6 billion in 1986. It was followed by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with $ 5.3 billion, down from $ 5.4 billion a year earlier; and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, $ 4.1 billion, up from $ 1.4 billion. Investment by all European nations dropped to $ 19.5 billion from $ 21.1 billion. Canadian investment, which was $ 6.5 billion in 1986, was reported at $ 849 million last year. <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> cautioned that the figures for individual countries can swing widely from year to year based on a single large deal or on difficulties in collecting information. The largest investment, by industry group, was in manufacturing _ particularly chemical and food companies _ at $ 16.3 billion, down 6 percent from 1986. Overseas investment in banking and finance dipped to $ 1.9 billion from $ 2.1 billion. In retail trade, purchases by foreigners totaled $ 682 million, a big drop from $ 5.2 billion in 1986. Real estate investment was $ 2.9 billion in 1987, down from $ 5.2 billion. According to the report, much of the Japanese investment was concentrated in real estate, particularly <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> office buildings and hotels in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
