<HEAD>Prices Higher at Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices were pushing higher at midday Wednesday as dealers took heart from sharp gains on overseas equity markets. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 20 points, or 1.1 percent, at 1,804.4 at 12:30 p.m. local time. Trading volume continued to disappoint the market, as a light 266.2 million shares changing hands by midday, compared with 224.3 million shares at the same time Tuesday. Wednesday's midday rise followed a 74.68-point jump in the Dow Jones industrial average to 2,031.12 on Tuesday and a 287.21-point gain in the Nikkei Index in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to 27,703.91 Wednesday. A 19.56-point advance in the Hang Seng index in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to 2,516.24 also heartened market players, several analysts said. The market `` seems to be rejoicing in the gains overnight in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>,'' one dealer said. However, several analysts were skeptical of the recovery and were n't convinced that the market had turned a corner. `` I'm not prepared to say that we're out of the woods quite yet,'' one equity strategist for a major <LOCATION> U.K. </LOCATION> brokerage said. International stocks, including chemical and pharmaceutical issues, were helped by a sinking pound, dealers said.
