<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities have risen to the highest level since the October stock market crash. In Tuesday's auction, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 6.4 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.53 percent, up from 6.34 percent last week. Another $ 6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.83 percent, up from 6.71 percent last week. The rates were the highest since Oct. 19 when three-month bills sold for 6.84 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.21 percent. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 6.73 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,834.90 and 7.17 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,654.70. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages increased to 7.58 percent last week, up from 7.40 percent the previous week.
