general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s maple syrup industry is threatened by an insect that usually chews on fruit trees but has found sugar maples more to its liking this spring, a plant expert says. `` If you've got a maple tree, you're in trouble,'' said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tattar </PERSON>, a plant pathologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> Widespread defoliation blamed on the insect _ called a pear thrips _ has been reported across <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in the past 10 days, he said Tuesday. `` It's everywhere from <LOCATION> Litchfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, to eastern and western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and the hills of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Tattar </PERSON> said. `` And we just do n't know very much about it. We never had a population blowup of the insect similar to this.'' The pear thrips was introduced into <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1904 and found its way from there into <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> cherry, apple and pear orchards, he said. `` I'm looking out of my window and I can see bare tops all over the hills,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` This certainly will have an adverse effect on next season's production.'' After four years of early thaws that cut short the sugaring season and sent prices of syrup to nearly $ 40 a gallon, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> maple sugar producers reported near-normal yields from their taps this spring. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> annually produces about 50,000 gallons of syrup. <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, the nation's largest maple sugar producer, averages about 500,000 gallons.
