<HEAD>Housing Industry Slowed By Rising Interest Rates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, Higher rates ... last fall., to clarify that
contract total is an annual rate.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rising interest rates have come knocking on the housing and construction industries, threatening to blow down five straight years of solid gains in nationwide sales. But economists say the cyclical `` big bad wolf'' is n't likely to cause too much damage in 1988, although the outlook for the next couple of years remains in question. `` It will be a weaker year than it could have been because of interest rates ... but we're still expecting a good year,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON> estimated that sales of existing homes would total 3.3 million and new home sales would total 650,000 in 1988, down from 3.65 million and 690,000 respectively last year 1987, but still among the strongest years this decade. A report released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> departments said that new-home sales climbed 4 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 679,000 _ the third consecutive rise and the fastest pace since new homes sold at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987. In a report last week, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing homes rose 4.5 percent last month after increases of 2.5 percent in both March and February. While economists said the reports show solid gains, they cautioned that consumers rushed to do their buying then before interest rates headed higher. They said May might not be as strong. `` People are trying to negotiate a settlement and get a mortgage in the face of a fairly certain rise in interest rates,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, chief economist with the F.W. Dodge Division of <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Mortgage rates are actually slightly lower now than they were a year ago _ averaging about 10.46 percent for a 30-year fixed-rate conventional mortgage, vs. an average 10.60 percent in May 1987, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> But after falling sharply since the Oct. 19 stock market crash, rates started to creep up again over the past several weeks on fears that the economy may be overheating and inflation might be on the rise. The 30-year mortgage rate, for instance, has risen more than half a percentage point since February, when it averaged 9.89 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> said. Many economists predict mortgage rates will continue to rise through the summer and top 11 percent by the end of the year. A handful are forecasting rates in excess of 12 percent in 1989. At the same time, experts are calling for moderate inflation of around 5 percent this year. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Nothaft </PERSON>, deputy chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>, said the rise in fixed-rate mortgages may cause some would-be homebuyers to switch to adjustable rate mortgages. He said some savings and loan associations also will become more accommodative, for instance, by requiring smaller down payments or lowering closing costs to encourage sales. <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON> also remains optimistic. He said that the `` Baby Boomers,'' the large segment of the population born after World War II, should remain interested in home buying as their families and incomes expand. But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Resler </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I think we're heading downhill in this industry, and eventually the fate of the housing market ... will filter through the rest of the economy as well. `` New homes need to be furnished with durable goods, like refrigerators or washers and dryers,'' he said. The higher rates also threaten new construction contracts, including residential and non-residential units, said <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>. F.W. Dodge reported Tuesday that contracting for new projects declined 6 percent in April from the previous month to an annual rate of $ 226.97 billion, extending a downward slide that began last fall. <PERSON> Bhristie </PERSON> said high vacancy rates in commercial properties, particularly offices and apartments, were responsible for reversing the industry's five-year upswing. But he said rising interest rates will only aggravate the situation since they translate to higher borrowing costs for contractors. `` The export boom which is pumping up the 1988 economy is n't much help to the construction industry, and could even prove troublesome,'' <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> said `` As economic activity heats up, rising interest rates imply still lower building later in the year.''
