<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A rash of good news greeted investors today in the form of a rejuvenated stock market, reports of steady growth in the economy and a perception that interest rates may have stopped rising. On Wall Street the Dow Jones industrial average, which on Tuesday shattered a prolonged post-crash lull by surging nearly 75 points, was up another 13 points by late morning. Broader market indices also extended gains. Also today, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that its chief forecasting gauge of economic activity rose a moderate 0.2 percent in April, signaling solid growth but no danger of recession this year. Economists said the performance of the Index of Leading Indicators was consistent with their belief that the economy was headed for its best year since 1984, as smokestack <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> benefits from a boom in export sales. That strength also was reflected in another <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report today that showed orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories rose a strong 1.2 percent in April, the second straight substantial monthly gain. The strength came in electrical machinery, lumber and wood products and in petroleum, chemicals and paper. A third <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report showed construction spending rose 0.1 percent in April, the slowest pace since January. But the figure masked a big rise in factory investment, which was offset by a decline in public spending. Industrial construction is now 39.1 percent higher than a year ago. In recent weeks the financial markets have interpreted signs of surging <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic strength as a harbinger of inflation and rising interest rates, eroding stock and bond prices. But after the three-day Memorial Day weekend investors seemed to reject that view and rushed back to buy stocks and bonds. The spree pushed the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average to its second-biggest gain of 1988. The closely watched blue-chip barometer climbed 74.68 points Tuesday to 2,031.12 _ the highest level since it closed at 2,036.31 on May 4. It was the biggest one-day advance in the Dow average since a 76.42 point gain on Jan. 4, the first trading day of the year, and the sixth-largest rise ever. The rally in the Dow was so strong that a voluntary limit on computerized program trading was triggered when the average's rise swept past 50 points in the last hour of trading. But even after the so-called `` collar'' went into effect for the rest of the day, the blue-chip average extended its gain. New confidence about the near-term outlook for inflation also pushed interest rates lower and lifted bond prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year bond closed about | point higher, or $ 6.25 for every $ 1,000 in face value, while its yield dropped to 9.23 percent from 9.31 percent late Friday Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities, however, rose in a government auction to the highest level since the October stock market crash. In other economic developments Tuesday: = The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that prices farmers got for raw products in May averaged 3.1 percent over April levels and were 4.7 percent over their mark for the same month last year = Contracting for new construction projects declined 6 percent in April from March, extending a downward slide that began last fall, according to a survey by the F.W Dodge Division of <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> = The government said foreign purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies dropped 22 percent to $ 30.5 billion in 1987, the first dip since 1983 in the rush by overseas investors to acquire <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets The government reported that new single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 679,000 last month, the fastest pace since new homes sold at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987. It was the third consecutive increase, coming atop a 1.2 percent rise in March and an 11.4 percent jump in February.
