<HEAD>Toyota Executive Says Decision On U.S. Firm Is Near</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will decide soon whether to build a truck plant in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a move that would halt Japanese truck exports to the American market, a <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> executive said. Negotiations have `` progressed to a rather considerable extent'' and a decision is expected soon, <PERSON> Tsutomu </PERSON> <PERSON> Oshima </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview in today's <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times. Such a move would result in the end of <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s truck exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said. Although he refused to disclose the export value of Toyota trucks, he said the company sent 280,000 pickup trucks to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year, with an average retail value of $ 9,000. Sites under consideration for the plant, <PERSON> Oshima </PERSON> said, include <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> operates a joint venture producing passenger cars with <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Georgetown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> just opened an independent passenger car production plant; or a new location. Start-up costs could eliminate the possiblity of a new location, <PERSON> Oshima </PERSON> said. `` Before the yen started appreciating in value, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> developed the -LRB- small -RRB- pickup market in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Even with a 25 percent tariff, we could sell our trucks at inexpensive prices,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> has been forced to raise its retail truck prices an average of 26.7 percent since 1985 and the prices `` have become a burden on the user,'' <PERSON> Oshima </PERSON> said. American sales of Toyota trucks totaled about 250,000 in 1987, down 30,000 from 1986. This year, sales have continued to decline, <PERSON> Oshima </PERSON> said.
