<HEAD>OECD Forecasts Interest Rate Rise for U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates could rise further in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the coming months, and there is little likelihood of any easing of rates in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is the only member of the `` Group of Seven'' industrialized countries where the cost of credit is expected to decline, the <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> said in the latest issue of its publication Financial Market Trends. The interest rate outlook for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is less clear because it depends on how the government allows the pound to move in relation to other currencies, the report said. The <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION>'s observation on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rates was made before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> tightened credit last week by pressuring up the overnight rate charged among banks for overnight loans to meet reserve requirements. The <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> said it based its forecast for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rates on concerns about a pickup of inflationary pressures, strong credit demand and the country's large trade deficit. Total credit demand in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is expected to strengthen over the coming months as the economy's expansion continues, chiefly due to an anticipated steep rise in corporate borrowing, the <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> said. Turning to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the organization observed that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s trade gap widened sharply in the first quarter While stemming the deficit `` would perhaps require bringing the pound to a more competitive level, implying lower interest rates,'' such a move would clash with the government's anti-inflation policy, the report said. The <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> predicted all major segments of Japanese financial markets would remain very active in the coming months, suggesting that the growing financing needs of the economy `` should be met without any particular strain on current credit conditions.'' `` The scope for lower rates remains limited,'' because <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s money supply is already expanding at an unprecedented rate, and its possible inflationary implications are giving rise to concern, the report said West German interest rates are also unlikely to come down further because of the strength of overall loan demand and growth in the money supply that is running ahead of the target rate, the <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> said.
