<FIRST>r f AM-SocializedElectricity     06-01 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Socialized Electricity,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Edison Launches Energy Cooperative That Relies on Peer
Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A kind of socialism is being tried by a group of <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s biggest commercial customers that have agreed to cooperate with each other to ease energy consumption. Under a year-long trial that began Wednesday, 10 <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> customers will work together to decide which should forfeit some electrical power during peak demand periods. They might do this by, for example, shutting off a bank of elevators or turning off the hot water for a few hours. As a result the utility estimates it could save 10 megawatts, or enough to meet a year's electrical needs in 5,000 homes. <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> has 640,000 residential and business customers in 40 cities and towns within a 30-mile radius of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. In addition to cutting back their electricity bill, the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION>, as the group is called, will be paid as if they are electricity providers. That's not new, however. What is different is that the arrangement combines peer pressure and altruism to save money and energy. To reinforce the cooperative spirit, each member of the group will be `` graded'' by the other members. If successful, the experiment will generate long-term contracts and more companies will be invited to join the cooperative. The cooperative will be headed for its first year by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, a former engineer who heads the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, which runs eight such utility cooperatives. `` The era of building -LRB- power -RRB- plants is over and the time for better utilization of resources is here,'' he said at a news conference explaining the cooperative plan, which he said also is being used on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. A self-described arch-conservative, <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said in an interview later that he has explained the dea to visiting planners from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. He said they all found the notion novel. `` What we have here is ... a democratic society in a more socialist environment,'' he said. `` You ca n't force people to do things.'' <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Reznicek </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION>, said the experiment is an attempt to deal with changes in demand for power. `` We have been an industry in a supply side mentality. That strategy has been a high-cost strategy,'' he said. `` Intelligent people stop and take a look and say there has to be a better way.''
</TEXT>
