<HEAD>Fina Hopes To Fuel Distributors' Initiative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has unveiled an incentive plan in its 22-state gasoline distribution network that will give independent distributors as much as $ 35,000 annually in retirement benefits. Under the plan, which analysts say is unprecedented in the industry, distributors who buy at least 2 million gallons of fuel annually can receive retirement benefits of $ 10,000 per year. Those who purchase 30 million gallons per year or more can be eligible to receive up to $ 35,000 per year in benefits. The benefits accrue to the owners of the <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION> distributorships or to the employees they designate, officials said Tuesday. `` This will motivate our jobbers to do a better job for themselves as well as for <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president of marketing and developer of the plan. Analysts said the move also will help the company polish the outdated image of some locations and upgrade a retail network that includes gas stations in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. `` I think it benefits the company and the dealers,'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Sudol </PERSON>, investment analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Fitch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. She called the retirement plan an imaginative `` carrot-and-stick approach'' that will require distributors to improve the quality of their stations to take advantage of the retirement program. The retirement program, which began Wednesday and runs through May 1993, is provided at no cost to the distributors, although they must meet certain company-imposed requirements. <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION>, a unit of Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petrofina </ORGANIZATION>, has about 4,000 service stations nationwide. To be eligible, distributors must buy at least 2 million gallons of gasoline or other refined products annually from the parent company and reinvest available building funds in accordance with <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION>'s ongoing building program. Retirement fund participants also are required to increase their fuel purchases by at least 5 percent through May 31, 1989. Similar annual requirements must be met for distributors to continue in the program until its expiration on May 31, 1993. All of <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION>'s 460 distributors who own or operate about 3,850 stations in 22 states are eligible for the program, <PERSON> Pearman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pearman </PERSON> said the program is being financed through several insurance companies and other lenders and that <ORGANIZATION> Fina </ORGANIZATION> may decide to continue the program after the initial five-year period. The retirement benefits are guaranteed for the qualified participant for life and are payable starting June 1, 1998, but not before the participant reaches 65.
