<FIRST>u f AM-MysteriousMarket Bjt   06-01 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mysterious Market, Bjt,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Watchers Confounded by Market's Mysterious Joy Ride</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you've been hearing for weeks about the post-crash stock market's malaise, you're probably wondering what has sent prices surging higher so suddenly. Welcome to the crowd. Seasoned market watchers expressed surprise at the buying spree following the long Memorial Day weekend that sent the languishing <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average up more than 100 points in two days. It soared nearly 75 points Tuesday, the biggest one-day rise since the beginning of the year, and tacked on 33 more on Wednesday. Many analysts said the rally once again proved the adage that you can not outguess the market. But some veteran economists warned that they saw no development that should so radically improve Wall Street's gloomy outlook for inflation and higher interest rates. Evidence of rising inflation persists, from the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> commodity pits to the neighborhood grocery checkout. Strains on <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s productive abilities, coupled with fears of a profound farm drought this summer, are intensifying upward pressure on prices. `` There's only one way to start writing this story: ` Once upon a time ...,''' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said in response to the stock market's abrupt `` It's a bit of a fairy tale out there.'' Explanations for the turnaround included speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will not tighten credit further, a realization that the economy is healthy, and a post-holiday tendency to buy stocks. Some economists said the market's reversal confirmed their view that inflation is not a big problem. A few even suggested President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s performance at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit injected a euphoric mood into the market that has n't been seen since last summer, well before the stunning collapse of Oct. 19 But others said they simply did not know why the market had reversed course. `` It's a very good question,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stovall </PERSON>, a New York-based stock market forecaster. `` The serenity could be short-lived. Everything that's happened has been given a positive bias or ignored.'' Some economists who scrutinize the links between markets were disturbed by Wall Street's big gain, partly because it defied a logical pattern that had developed between stocks, bonds and commodity prices. In that relationship, when commodity prices rise, bonds fall over the consequent fear of inflation and depress stocks as well. But on Tuesday, commodity prices jumped _ while stocks and bonds also rose. `` On balance, what's going on with the stock and bond markets does not ring true,'' <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said. `` The trap door is going to open up again and suck everybody down.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON>, chief economist at <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, speculated the Wall Street rally reflected growing investor hopes of no further moves to tighten credit by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. He said rising commodity prices were based on fear of drought, not a broad inflationary move. `` In that environment, inflation fears subside and the market can do a bit better,'' <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> already has moved a few times this year to nudge interest rates higher through its control of the amount of money in the banking system. There had been speculation last week that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> would take a more drastic step by announcing an increase in the discount rate, the loan fee it charges financial institutions. The rate has remained at 6 percent since Sept. 4. Some market watchers said it was pointless to speculate about the short-term ups and downs of stock prices because meaningful trends can only be detected over a long period. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobel </PERSON>, a Wall Street historian and professor who has written several books on the market, said he would advise investors to ignore most economists' predictions of stock behavior because they are so unreliable. `` They'd be better off using <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s astrologist,'' <PERSON> Sobel </PERSON> said. `` I think these people are vastly overpaid. They do n't know what they're doing most of the time.''
