<HEAD>German Police Arrive To Escort Fugitive Home To Face Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A West German fugitive accused of defrauding <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> of more than $ 280 million will be escorted home Friday by federal German police, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities said Wednesday. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Joachim </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON>, 38, a former currency trader from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, has exhausted his extradition appeals, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney's Office. In the warrant for <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON>'s arrest and the extradition request, he is charged with forgery of documents and instigation of embezzlement in a scheme in which employees of <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagenwerk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> were persuaded to enter into foreign currency transactions as part of a secret profit-sharing agreement. <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> was arrested on a fugitive warrant in November 1987 at his <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> apartment, where he was living under an assumed name. A special team of West German federal police was created a year ago to hunt for <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON>, who fled in March 1987 after the discovery of alleged fraudulent foreign exchange deals that cost <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> about $ 282.4 million. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> said it first discovered the fraud when the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hungary </ORGANIZATION> refused to honor a contract calling on it to buy dollars from <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION>. While he was a fugitive, <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> traveled through <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, several southern European countries and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, West German police said. Prosecutors in the northern West German city of <LOCATION> Braunschweig </LOCATION> have alleged that <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> and several former <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> employees defrauded the giant automaker by falsifying financial instruments known as forward contracts. Such contracts are used by large international companies like <PERSON> Volkswaggen </PERSON> to protect themselves from currency fluctuations. <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> is accused of putting profits from the currency exchange deals into secret bank accounts in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON>.
