<HEAD>SEC Allows Month To Air Objections To Proposed Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> decided Wednesday to give securities industry officials a month to press their objections to a proposal aimed at protecting investors' option to sue their brokers The commission had been scheduled to vote to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to pass a law barring brokerage firms from requiring customers to agree in advance to submit disputes to stock exchange-sponsored arbitration panels. But the vote was postponed after commissioners <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Grundfest </PERSON> said the matter required more deliberation. Commissioners agreed to decide the matter during the first week of July, before one of the advocates of the change, <PERSON> Aulana </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, leaves the commission. <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> argued it was unfair to require investors to give up the right to sue before they have any idea of the nature or size of a dispute that may later arise. <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> also said that providing an alternative to arbitration will serve as an incentive to keeping the system fair. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said he was inclined to support <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> but wanted to give the brokerage firms a chance to argue their case. A survey by the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> staff of 65 firms, handling 90 percent of all customer accounts, showed that virtually all require customers to arbitrate disputes, particularly customers who borrow money through margin accounts or trade in stock options. The <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a group of state regulators, has been pressing to do away with mandatory arbitration clauses. Staff members of the finance subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> are working on an arbitration bill that would, among other things, forbid forced arbitration. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, representing brokerage firms, says it is unfair to dictate to brokers how they must do business and that it makes little sense to force cases on an overburdened and costly court system.
