PERSON>'s legal department seeking comment on the lawsuit was not returned Wednesday. A <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> spokesman, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Horne </PERSON>, said, `` We remain optimistic about the deal and we intend to close the transaction as soon as possible.,'' <PERSON> Lipton </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Englewood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cliffs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, is owned by the Dutch-English company <ORGANIZATION> Unilever </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> It markets <LOCATION> Lipton </LOCATION> and Oriental Treasures herbal teas and is the dominant company in traditional black teas with more than 50 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. Celestial Seasonings, purchased by <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON> in 1984, accounts for more than half of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> herbal tea sales, according to <PERSON> Bigelow </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Glenview </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, had sales of $ 9.9 billion in 1987, <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> said. The proposed sale of Celestial Seasoings was announced in December 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing the proposed sale, <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> said.
