<HEAD>Ethanol Producers File Lawsuit Against Oil Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven ethanol producers filed a $ 2.1 billion antitrust lawsuit in <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday, alleging that four major oil companies conspired to discourage the sale of ethanol. The defendants are <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Marathon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, one of the attorneys who filed the lawsuit, charged that the oil companies made inaccurate and misleading statements against gasohol _ a blend of 10 percent ethanol and 90 percent gasoline `` The clearest evidence of what the oil companies have done is labeling,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said at a news conference. He said signs at some of the oil companies' service stations say: `` Our gasoline contains no alcohol or ethanol,'' or `` Our gasoline is clean.'' `` Those sorts of signs and labels would clearly infer ... there is something wrong with alcohol or ethanol,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. Spokespeople for the oil companies had no immediate comment. As a result of the oil companies' campaign, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the ethanol market has `` effectively dried up,'' with producers suffering significant economic damages. The plaintiffs include <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rockford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Shepherd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>.; <ORGANIZATION> Vidalia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethanol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of Vidalia, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>.; <ORGANIZATION> Alpebo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>.; <ORGANIZATION> Shreveport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethanol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>.; <ORGANIZATION> Lakefield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethanol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lakefield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont </LOCATION><LOCATION> . </LOCATION> Ethanol is made from corn, and if the ethanol industry had been allowed to grow, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said it would have had a `` tremendous effect on agriculture.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said ethanol also is good for the environment since it can reduce harmful emissions from automobile exhausts. The lawsuit also said the defendants refused to accept credit-card invoices from gasohol sales and terminated some retailers or distributors who did accept credit-card invoices for gasohol purchases. The companies also limited the availability of gasohol to consumers and refused to communicate or deal directly with the plaintiffs, the lawsuit contended. The ethanol manufacturers are asking for three times their actual damages of $ 700 million and for an injunction to stop the defendants from engaging in practices allegedly designed to hurt the ethanol market. `` Where this industry be without oil companies negatively advertising against our product would be speculation, but I believe it would be a lot larger,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Wentworth </PERSON>, first vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` The bottom line here is market-share. The major oil companies do n't want to give it up to independent blenders.''
</TEXT>
