<HEAD>Japan's Prime Minister Calls For Increased Mutual Trade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> said on Wednesday it `` goes without saying'' that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> must keep trying to open its markets wider to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He promptly added that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will be trying to increase its own exports. He refused to say, however, what he thought the appropriate exchange rate should be between the dollar and the yen, commenting that `` God only knows'' the answer. Earlier Wednesday, the dollar weakened briefly in morning trading in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> after <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> governor <PERSON> Satoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> told reporters he thought a long-term rise in the dollar was unlikely. But the dollar soon recovered, closing in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Wednesday at 125.23 yen, up from 124.80 yen on Tuesday. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> held a news conference in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after addressing the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s special session on disarmament. Asked about the balance of trade between <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> replied: `` It goes without saying that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> must continue with further efforts to open up the Japanese markets even more. Having said that, I should also like to add that there will be greater efforts to export <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s goods.'' He was less forthcoming about the outlook for exhange rates. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> will soon be meeting in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Western allies for an economic summit, where the subject is likely to arise. He said that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> considers the Louvre Accord, which deals with policy coordination among the major countries on exchange rates, `` has been proceeding smoothly.'' `` As for that other question, what level of the exchange rate we think is most appropriate, I myself as well as our finance minister make it the rule to say that ` It is something that God only knows,''' the prime minister remarked. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> spoke in Japanese, aided by an interpreter. He declined to characterize progress on another thorny U.S.-Japanese trade issue _ <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to sell more beef and citrus products in the highly protective Japanese market. Noting that bilateral talks on the issue were under way, he said he did not want to prejudice the negotiations and would offer no comment. Earlier Wednesday, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> pledged increased efforts by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in the cause of disarmament and world peace, including sending Japanese technicians and advisers to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to monitor elections and to repair transportation, communication and medical services. He congratulated President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on achieving the intermediate-range nuclear forces -LRB- INF -RRB- treaty scrapping medium and shorter-range nuclear missles, which took effect Wednesday. At the same time, he enunciated a Japanese policy of cautious disarmament based on negotiation. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> is scheduled to meet <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Friday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where the president will brief Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> on the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit.
